# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-structures
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] In computer science, an **array** is a data structure consisting of a collection of *elements* (values or variables), of the same memory size, each identified by at least one *array index* or *key*, the collection of which may be a tuple, known as an index tuple.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] In general, an array is a mutable and linear collection of elements with the same data type.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] An array is stored such that the position (memory address) of each element can be computed from its index tuple by a mathematical formula.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The simplest type of data structure is a linear array, also called a one-dimensional array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For example, an array of ten 32-bit (4-byte) integer variables, with indices 0 through 9, may be stored as ten words at memory addresses 2000, 2004, 2008, ..., 2036, (in hexadecimal: `0x7D0`, `0x7D4`, `0x7D8`, ..., `0x7F4`) so that the element with index *i* has the address 2000 + (*i* × 4).
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The memory address of the first element of an array is called first address, foundation address, or base address.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Because the mathematical concept of a matrix can be represented as a two-dimensional grid, two-dimensional arrays are also sometimes called "matrices".
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] In some cases the term "vector" is used in computing to refer to an array, although tuples rather than vectors are the more mathematically correct equivalent.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Tables are often implemented in the form of arrays, especially lookup tables; the word "table" is sometimes used as a synonym of array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Arrays are among the oldest and most important data structures, and are used by almost every program.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] They are also used to implement many other data structures, such as lists and strings.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] They effectively exploit the addressing logic of computers.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] In most modern computers and many external storage devices, the memory is a one-dimensional array of words, whose indices are their addresses.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Processors, especially vector processors, are often optimized for array operations.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Arrays are useful mostly because the element indices can be computed at run time.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Among other things, this feature allows a single iterative statement to process arbitrarily many elements of an array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For that reason, the elements of an array data structure are required to have the same size and should use the same data representation.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The set of valid index tuples and the addresses of the elements (and hence the element addressing formula) are usually, but not always, fixed while the array is in use.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The term "array" may also refer to an array data type, a kind of data type provided by most high-level programming languages that consists of a collection of values or variables that can be selected by one or more indices computed at run-time.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Array types are often implemented by array structures; however, in some languages they may be implemented by hash tables, linked lists, search trees, or other data structures.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The term is also used, especially in the description of algorithms, to mean associative array or "abstract array", a theoretical computer science model (an abstract data type or ADT) intended to capture the essential properties of arrays.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The first digital computers used machine-language programming to set up and access array structures for data tables, vector and matrix computations, and for many other purposes.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] John von Neumann wrote the first array-sorting program (merge sort) in 1945, during the building of the first stored-program computer.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Array indexing was originally done by self-modifying code, and later using index registers and indirect addressing.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Some mainframes designed in the 1960s, such as the Burroughs B5000 and its successors, used memory segmentation to perform index-bounds checking in hardware.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Assembly languages generally have no special support for arrays, other than what the machine itself provides.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The earliest high-level programming languages, including FORTRAN (1957), Lisp (1958), COBOL (1960), and ALGOL 60 (1960), had support for multi-dimensional arrays, and so has C (1972).
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] In C++ (1983), class templates exist for multi-dimensional arrays whose dimension is fixed at runtime as well as for runtime-flexible arrays.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Arrays are used to implement mathematical vectors and matrices, as well as other kinds of rectangular tables.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Many databases, small and large, consist of (or include) one-dimensional arrays whose elements are records.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Arrays are used to implement other data structures, such as lists, heaps, hash tables, deques, queues, stacks, strings, and VLists.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] One or more large arrays are sometimes used to emulate in-program dynamic memory allocation, particularly memory pool allocation.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Historically, this has sometimes been the only way to allocate "dynamic memory" portably.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Arrays can be used to determine partial or complete control flow in programs, as a compact alternative to (otherwise repetitive) multiple `IF` statements.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] In this context, they are known as control tables and are used in conjunction with a purpose-built interpreter whose control flow is altered according to values contained in the array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The array may contain subroutine pointers (or relative subroutine numbers that can be acted upon by SWITCH statements) that direct the path of the execution of the program.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] When data objects are stored in an array, individual objects are selected by an index that is usually a non-negative scalar integer.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] An index *maps* the array value to a stored object.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The first element of the array is indexed by subscript of 0.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The first element of the array is indexed by subscript of 1.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The base index of an array can be freely chosen.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Using zero based indexing is the design choice of many influential programming languages, including C, Java and Lisp.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] This leads to simpler implementation where the subscript refers to an offset from the starting position of an array, so the first element has an offset of zero.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Arrays can have multiple dimensions, thus it is not uncommon to access an array using multiple indices.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For example, a two-dimensional array `A` with three rows and four columns might provide access to the element at the 2nd row and 4th column by the expression `A[1][3]` in the case of a zero-based indexing system.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Thus two indices are used for a two-dimensional array, three for a three-dimensional array, and *n* for an *n*-dimensional array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The number of indices needed to specify an element is called the dimension, dimensionality, or rank of the array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] In standard arrays, each index is restricted to a certain range of consecutive integers (or consecutive values of some enumerated type), and the address of an element is computed by a "linear" formula on the indices.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] A one-dimensional array (or single dimension array) is a type of linear array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Accessing its elements involves a single subscript which can either represent a row or column index.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] As an example consider the C declaration `int a[10];` which declares a one-dimensional array named `a` of ten integers.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Here, the array can store ten elements of type `int` .
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] This array has indices starting from zero through nine.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For example, the expressions `a[0]` and `a[9]` are the first and last elements respectively.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For a vector with linear addressing, the element with index *i* is located at the address *B* + *c* · *i*, where *B* is a fixed *base address* and *c* a fixed constant, sometimes called the *address increment* or *stride*.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] If the valid element indices begin at 0, the constant *B* is simply the address of the first element of the array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For this reason, the C programming language specifies that array indices always begin at 0; and many programmers will call that element "zeroth" rather than "first".
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] However, one can choose the index of the first element by an appropriate choice of the base address *B*.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For example, if the array has five elements, indexed 1 through 5, and the base address *B* is replaced by *B* + 30*c*, then the indices of those same elements will be 31 to 35.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] If the numbering does not start at 0, the constant *B* may not be the address of any element.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For a multidimensional array, the element with indices *i*,*j* would have address *B* + *c* · *i* + *d* · *j*, where the coefficients *c* and *d* are the *row* and *column address increments*, respectively.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] This means that array a has 2 rows and 3 columns, and the array is of integer type.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Here we can store 6 elements they will be stored linearly but starting from first row linear then continuing with second row.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] This formula requires only *k* multiplications and *k* additions, for any array that can fit in memory.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Moreover, if any coefficient is a fixed power of 2, the multiplication can be replaced by bit shifting.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The coefficients *c**k* must be chosen so that every valid index tuple maps to the address of a distinct element.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] If the minimum legal value for every index is 0, then *B* is the address of the element whose indices are all zero.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] As in the one-dimensional case, the element indices may be changed by changing the base address *B*.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Thus, if a two-dimensional array has rows and columns indexed from 1 to 10 and 1 to 20, respectively, then replacing *B* by *B* + *c*1 − 3*c*2 will cause them to be renumbered from 0 through 9 and 4 through 23, respectively.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Taking advantage of this feature, some languages (like FORTRAN 77) specify that array indices begin at 1, as in mathematical tradition while other languages (like Fortran 90, Pascal and Algol) let the user choose the minimum value for each index.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The addressing formula is completely defined by the dimension *d*, the base address *B*, and the increments *c*1, *c*2, ..., *c**k*.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] It is often useful to pack these parameters into a record called the array's descriptor, stride vector, or dope vector.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The size of each element, and the minimum and maximum values allowed for each index may also be included in the dope vector.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The dope vector is a complete handle for the array, and is a convenient way to pass arrays as arguments to procedures.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Many useful array slicing operations (such as selecting a sub-array, swapping indices, or reversing the direction of the indices) can be performed very efficiently by manipulating the dope vector.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Often the coefficients are chosen so that the elements occupy a contiguous area of memory.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Even if arrays are always created with contiguous elements, some array slicing operations may create non-contiguous sub-arrays from them.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] There are two systematic compact layouts for a two-dimensional array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For arrays with three or more indices, "row major order" puts in consecutive positions any two elements whose index tuples differ only by one in the *last* index.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] "Column major order" is analogous with respect to the *first* index.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] In systems which use processor cache or virtual memory, scanning an array is much faster if successive elements are stored in consecutive positions in memory, rather than sparsely scattered.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] This is known as spatial locality, which is a type of locality of reference.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Many algorithms that use multidimensional arrays will scan them in a predictable order.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] A programmer (or a sophisticated compiler) may use this information to choose between row- or column-major layout for each array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For example, when computing the product *A*·*B* of two matrices, it would be best to have *A* stored in row-major order, and *B* in column-major order.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Static arrays have a size that is fixed when they are created and consequently do not allow elements to be inserted or removed.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] However, by allocating a new array and copying the contents of the old array to it, it is possible to effectively implement a *dynamic* version of an array; see dynamic array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] If this operation is done infrequently, insertions at the end of the array require only amortized constant time.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Some array data structures do not reallocate storage, but do store a count of the number of elements of the array in use, called the count or size.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] This effectively makes the array a dynamic array with a fixed maximum size or capacity; Pascal strings are examples of this.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] More complicated (non-linear) formulas are occasionally used.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For a compact two-dimensional triangular array, for instance, the addressing formula is a polynomial of degree 2.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Both *store* and *select* take (deterministic worst case) constant time.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Arrays take linear (O(*n*)) space in the number of elements *n* that they hold.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] In an array with element size *k* and on a machine with a cache line size of B bytes, iterating through an array of *n* elements requires the minimum of ceiling(*nk*/B) cache misses, because its elements occupy contiguous memory locations.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] This is roughly a factor of B/*k* better than the number of cache misses needed to access *n* elements at random memory locations.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Libraries provide low-level optimized facilities for copying ranges of memory (such as memcpy) which can be used to move contiguous blocks of array elements significantly faster than can be achieved through individual element access.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The speedup of such optimized routines varies by array element size, architecture, and implementation.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Memory-wise, arrays are compact data structures with no per-element overhead.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] There may be a per-array overhead (e.g., to store index bounds) but this is language-dependent.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] It can also happen that elements stored in an array require *less* memory than the same elements stored in individual variables, because several array elements can be stored in a single word; such arrays are often called *packed* arrays.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] An extreme (but commonly used) case is the bit array, where every bit represents a single element.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] A single octet can thus hold up to 256 different combinations of up to 8 different conditions, in the most compact form.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Array accesses with statically predictable access patterns are a major source of data parallelism.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Dynamic arrays or growable arrays are similar to arrays but add the ability to insert and delete elements; adding and deleting at the end is particularly efficient.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] However, they reserve linear (Θ(*n*)) additional storage, whereas arrays do not reserve additional storage.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Associative arrays provide a mechanism for array-like functionality without huge storage overheads when the index values are sparse.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For example, an array that contains values only at indexes 1 and 2 billion may benefit from using such a structure.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Specialized associative arrays with integer keys include Patricia tries, Judy arrays, and van Emde Boas trees.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Balanced trees require O(log *n*) time for indexed access, but also permit inserting or deleting elements in O(log *n*) time, whereas growable arrays require linear (Θ(*n*)) time to insert or delete elements at an arbitrary position.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Linked lists allow constant time removal and insertion in the middle but take linear time for indexed access.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Their memory use is typically worse than arrays, but is still linear.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] An Iliffe vector is an alternative to a multidimensional array structure.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] It uses a one-dimensional array of references to arrays of one dimension less.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For two dimensions, in particular, this alternative structure would be a vector of pointers to vectors, one for each row(pointer on c or c++).
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Thus an element in row *i* and column *j* of an array *A* would be accessed by double indexing (*A*[*i*][*j*] in typical notation).
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] This alternative structure allows jagged arrays, where each row may have a different size—or, in general, where the valid range of each index depends on the values of all preceding indices.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] It also saves one multiplication (by the column address increment) replacing it by a bit shift (to index the vector of row pointers) and one extra memory access (fetching the row address), which may be worthwhile in some architectures.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] The *dimension* of an array is the number of indices needed to select an element.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Thus, if the array is seen as a function on a set of possible index combinations, it is the dimension of the space of which its domain is a discrete subset.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Thus a one-dimensional array is a list of data, a two-dimensional array is a rectangle of data, a three-dimensional array a block of data, etc.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] This should not be confused with the dimension of the set of all matrices with a given domain, that is, the number of elements in the array.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] For example, an array with 5 rows and 4 columns is two-dimensional, but such matrices form a 20-dimensional space.
[src:data-structures/array-data-structure] Similarly, a three-dimensional vector can be represented by a one-dimensional array of size three.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In computer science, a **B-tree** is a self-balancing tree data structure that maintains sorted data and allows searches, sequential access, insertions, and deletions in logarithmic time.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The B-tree generalizes the binary search tree, allowing nodes to have more than two children.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] By allowing more children under one node than a regular self-balancing binary search tree, the B-tree reduces the height of the tree and puts the data in fewer separate blocks.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This is especially important for trees stored in secondary storage (e.g., disk drives), as these systems have relatively high latency and work with relatively large blocks of data, hence the B-tree's use in databases and file systems.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This remains a major advantage when the tree is stored in memory, as modern computer systems rely heavily on CPU caches.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Compared to reading from the cache, reading from memory after a cache miss costs significant time.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] While working at Boeing Research Labs, Rudolf Bayer and Edward M.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] McCreight invented B-trees to efficiently manage index pages for large random-access files.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Their basic assumption was that indices would be so voluminous that only small chunks of the tree could fit in the main memory.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight's paper *Organization and maintenance of large ordered indices* was first circulated in July 1970 and later published in *Acta Informatica*.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight never explained what, if anything, the *B* stands for; *Boeing*, *balanced*, *between*, *broad*, *bushy*, and *Bayer* have been suggested.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Every node, except for the root and the leaves, has at least ⌈*m*/2⌉ children.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The root node has at least two children unless it is a leaf.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A non-leaf node with *k* children contains *k*−1 keys.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The keys of each non-leaf node act as separation values that divide its subtrees.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] For example, if an internal node has 3 child nodes (or subtrees), then it must have 2 keys: *a*1 and *a*2.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] All values in the leftmost subtree will be less than *a*1, all values in the middle subtree will be between *a*1 and *a*2, and all values in the rightmost subtree will be greater than *a*2.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] ) are all nodes except for leaf nodes and the root node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] They are usually represented as an ordered set of elements and child pointers.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] −1; therefore, each internal node is at least half full.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] implies that two half-full nodes can be joined to make a legal node, and one full node can be split into two legal nodes (if there's room to push one element up into the parent).
[src:data-structures/b-tree] These properties make it possible to delete and insert new values into a B-tree while also adjusting the tree to preserve its properties.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The root node's number of children has the same upper limit as internal nodes but has no lower limit.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] −1 elements in the entire tree, the root will be the only node in the tree with no children at all.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In Knuth's terminology, the "leaf" nodes are the actual data objects/chunks.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] /2-1 if they are not the root) and pointers (one for each key) to nodes carrying the data objects/chunks.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A B-tree of depth *n*+1 can hold about *U* times as many items as a B-tree of depth *n*, but the cost of search, insert, and delete operations grows with the depth of the tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] As with any balanced tree, the cost grows much more slowly than the number of elements.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Some balanced trees store values only at leaf nodes and use different kinds of nodes for leaf nodes and internal nodes.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] B-trees keep values in every node in the tree except leaf nodes.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The literature on B-trees is not uniform in its terminology.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight (1972), Comer (1979), and others define the **order** of a B-tree as the minimum number of keys in a non-root node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Folk and Zoellick point out that terminology is ambiguous because the maximum number of keys is unclear.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] An order 3 B-tree might hold a maximum of 6 keys or a maximum of 7 keys.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Knuth (1998) avoids the problem by defining the **order** to be the maximum number of children (which is one more than the maximum number of keys).
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight (1972) considered the leaf level to be the lowest level of keys, but Knuth considered the leaf level to be one level below the lowest keys.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] There are many possible implementation choices.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In some designs, the leaves may hold the entire data record; in other designs, the leaves may only hold pointers to the data record.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Those choices are not fundamental to the idea of a B-tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] For simplicity, most authors assume there is a fixed number of keys that fit in a node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The basic assumption is that the key size and node size are both fixed.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In practice, variable-length keys may be employed.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] As with other trees, B-trees can be represented as a collection of three types of nodes: *root*, *internal* (a.k.a. interior), and *leaf*.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] To maintain the predefined range of child nodes, internal nodes may be joined or split.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Usually, the number of keys is chosen to vary between d and $2d$ , where d is the minimum number of keys, and $d+1$ is the minimum degree or branching factor of the tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The factor of 2 will guarantee that nodes can be split or combined.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If an internal node has $2d$ keys, then adding a key to that node can be accomplished by splitting the hypothetical $2d+1$ key node into two d key nodes and moving the key that would have been in the middle to the parent node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Each split node has the required minimum number of keys.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Similarly, if an internal node and its neighbor each have d keys, then a key may be deleted from the internal node by combining it with its neighbor.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Deleting the key would make the internal node have $d-1$ keys; joining the neighbor would add d keys plus one more key brought down from the neighbor's parent.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The result is an entirely full node of $2d$ keys.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A B-tree is kept balanced after insertion by splitting a would-be overfilled node, of $2d+1$ keys, into two d-key siblings and inserting the mid-value key into the parent.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Depth only increases when the root is split, maintaining balance.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Similarly, a B-tree is kept balanced after deletion by merging or redistributing keys among siblings to maintain the d-key minimum for non-root nodes.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A merger reduces the number of keys in the parent, potentially forcing it to merge or redistribute keys with its siblings, and so on.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The only change in depth occurs when the root has two children, of d and (transitionally) $d-1$ keys, in which case the two siblings and parent are merged, reducing the depth by one.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This depth will increase slowly as elements are added to the tree, but an increase in the overall depth is infrequent, and results in all leaf nodes being one more node farther away from the root.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Because a range of child nodes is permitted, B-trees do not need re-balancing as frequently as other self-balancing search trees, but may waste some space since nodes are not entirely full.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] B-trees have substantial advantages over alternative implementations when the time to access the data of a node greatly exceeds the time spent processing that data, because the cost of accessing the node may then be amortized over multiple operations within the node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This usually occurs when the node data are stored in secondary storage, such as disk drives.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] By maximizing the number of keys within each internal node, the height of the tree decreases, and the number of expensive node accesses is reduced.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In addition, rebalancing of the tree occurs less frequently.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The maximum number of child nodes depends on the information that must be stored for each child node and the size of a full disk block or an analogous size in secondary storage.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] While 2–3 B-trees are easier to explain, practical B-trees using secondary storage need a large number of child nodes to improve performance.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The term **B-tree** may refer to a specific design or a general class of designs.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In the narrow sense, a B-tree stores keys in its internal nodes but need not store those keys in the records at the leaves.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The general class includes variations such as the B+ tree, the B* tree and the B*+ tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Sorting and searching algorithms can be characterized by the number of comparison operations that must be performed using order notation.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A binary search of a sorted table with N records, for example, can be done in roughly ⌈ log2 *N* ⌉ comparisons.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If the table had 1,000,000 records, then a specific record could be located with at most 20 comparisons: ⌈ log2 (1,000,000) ⌉ = 20.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Large databases have historically been kept on disk drives.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The time required to read a record on a disk drive far exceeds the time needed to compare keys once the record is available due to seek time and rotational delay.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The seek time may be 0 to 20 or more milliseconds, and the rotational delay averages about half the rotation period.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] For a 7200 RPM drive, the rotation period is 8.33 milliseconds.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] For a drive such as the Seagate ST3500320NS, the track-to-track seek time is 0.8 milliseconds and the average reading seek time is 8.5 milliseconds.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] For simplicity, assume reading from disk takes about 10 milliseconds.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The time required to locate one record out of a million in the example above would be 20 disk reads, each taking 10 milliseconds, which equals 0.2 seconds.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The search time is reduced because individual records are grouped together in a disk **block**.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A disk block might be 16 kilobytes in size.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If each record is 160 bytes, then 100 records could be stored in each block.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The disk read time above was actually for an entire block.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Once the disk head is in position, one or more disk blocks can be read with little delay.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] With 100 records per block, the last 6 or so comparisons don't need to do any disk reads—the comparisons are all within the last disk block read.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] To speed up the search further, the time to do the first 13 to 14 comparisons (which each required disk access) must be reduced.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A B-tree index can be used to improve performance.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A B-tree index creates a multi-level tree structure that breaks a database down into fixed-size blocks or pages.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Each level of this tree can be used to link those pages via an address location, allowing one page (known as a node, or internal page) to refer to another with leaf pages at the lowest level.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] One page is typically the starting point of the tree, or the "root".
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This is where the search for a particular key would begin, traversing a path that terminates in a leaf.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Most pages in this structure will be leaf pages which refer to specific table rows.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Because each node (or internal page) can have more than two children, a B-tree index will usually have a shorter height (the distance from the root to the farthest leaf) than a Binary Search Tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In the example above, initial disk reads narrowed the search range by a factor of two.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] That can be improved by creating an auxiliary index that contains the first record in each disk block (sometimes called a sparse index).
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This auxiliary index would be 1% of the size of the original database, but it can be searched quickly.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Finding an entry in the auxiliary index would tell us which block to search in the main database; after searching the auxiliary index, we would have to search only that one block of the main database—at a cost of one more disk read.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In the above example, the index would hold 10,000 entries and would take at most 14 comparisons to return a result.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Like the main database, the last six or so comparisons in the auxiliary index would be on the same disk block.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The index could be searched in about eight disk reads, and the desired record could be accessed in 9 disk reads.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Creating an auxiliary index can be repeated to make an auxiliary index to the auxiliary index.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] That would create an aux-aux index that would need only 100 entries and would fit in one disk block.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Instead of reading 14 disk blocks to find the desired record, we only need to read 3 blocks.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This blocking is the core idea behind the creation of the B-tree, where disk blocks form a hierarchy of levels to make up the index.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Reading and searching the first (and only) block of the aux-aux index, which is the root of the tree, identifies the relevant block in aux-index in the level below.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Reading and searching that aux-index block identifies the relevant block to read until the final level, known as the leaf level, identifies a record in the main database.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Instead of 150 milliseconds, we need only 30 milliseconds to get the record.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The auxiliary indices have turned the search problem from a binary search requiring roughly log2 *N* disk reads to one requiring only log*b* *N* disk reads where b is the blocking factor (the number of entries per block: *b* = 100 entries per block in our example; log100 1,000,000 = 3 reads).
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In practice, if the main database is being frequently searched, the aux-aux index and much of the aux index may reside in a disk cache, so they would not incur a disk read.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The B-tree remains the standard index implementation in almost all relational databases, and many nonrelational databases use it as well.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If the database does not change, then compiling the index is simple to do, and the index need never be changed.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If there are changes, managing the database and its index requires additional computation.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Deleting records from a database is relatively easy.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The index can stay the same, and the record can just be marked as deleted.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If there are a large number of lazy deletions, then searching and storage become less efficient.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Insertions can be very slow in a sorted sequential file because room for the inserted record must be made.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Inserting a record before the first record requires shifting all of the records down one.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Such an operation is just too expensive to be practical.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Instead of densely packing all the records in a block, the block can have some free space to allow for subsequent insertions.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Those spaces would be marked as if they were "deleted" records.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Both insertions and deletions are fast as long as space is available on a block.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If an insertion won't fit on the block, then some free space on some nearby block must be found and the auxiliary indices adjusted.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The best case is that enough space is available nearby so that the amount of block reorganization can be minimized.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Alternatively, some out-of-sequence disk blocks may be used.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The B-tree uses all of the ideas described above.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In addition, a B-tree minimizes waste by making sure the interior nodes are at least half full.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A B-tree can handle an arbitrary number of insertions and deletions.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Let *h* ≥ –1 be the height of the classic B-tree (see Tree (data structure) § Terminology for the tree height definition).
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Let *n* ≥ 0 be the number of entries in the tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Let *m* be the maximum number of children a node can have.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] It can be shown (by induction for example) that a B-tree of height *h* with all its nodes completely filled has *n* = *m**h*+1–1 entries.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Let d be the minimum number of children an internal (non-root) node must have.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Searching is similar to searching a binary search tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Starting at the root, the tree is recursively traversed from top to bottom.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] At each level, the search reduces its field of view to the child pointer (subtree) whose range includes the search value.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A subtree's range is defined by the values, or keys, contained in its parent node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] These limiting values are also known as separation values.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Binary search is typically (but not necessarily) used within nodes to find the separation values and child tree of interest.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] To insert a new element, search the tree to find the leaf node where the new element should be added.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Values less than the median are put in the new left node, and values greater than the median are put in the new right node, with the median acting as a separation value.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The separation value is inserted in the node's parent, which may cause it to be split, and so on.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If the node has no parent (i.e., the node was the root), create a new root above this node (increasing the height of the tree).
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If the splitting goes all the way up to the root, it creates a new root with a single separator value and two children, which is why the lower bound on the size of internal nodes does not apply to the root.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The maximum number of elements per node is *U*−1.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] When a node is split, one element moves to the parent, but one element is added.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] So, it must be possible to divide the maximum number *U*−1 of elements into two legal nodes.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If this number is odd, then *U*=2*L* and one of the new nodes contains (*U*−2)/2 = *L*−1 elements, and hence is a legal node, and the other contains one more element, and hence it is legal too.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If *U*−1 is even, then *U*=2*L*−1, so there are 2*L*−2 elements in the node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Half of this number is *L*−1, which is the minimum number of elements allowed per node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] An alternative algorithm supports a single pass down the tree from the root to the node where the insertion will take place, splitting any full nodes encountered on the way pre-emptively.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This prevents the need to recall the parent nodes into memory, which may be expensive if the nodes are on secondary storage.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] However, to use this algorithm, we must be able to send one element to the parent and split the remaining *U*−2 elements into two legal nodes, without adding a new element.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This requires *U* = 2*L* rather than *U* = 2*L*−1, which accounts for why some textbooks impose this requirement in defining B-trees.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] There are two popular strategies for deletion from a B-tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Do a single pass down the tree, but before entering (visiting) a node, restructure the tree so that once the key to be deleted is encountered, it can be deleted without triggering the need for any further restructuring.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The algorithm below uses the former strategy.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Deleting an element may put its node under the minimum number of elements and children.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The procedures for these cases are listed below.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If the value is in a leaf node, simply delete it from the node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If underflow happens, rebalance the tree as described in the section "Rebalancing after deletion" below.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Each element in an internal node acts as a separation value for two subtrees; we need to find a replacement for separation.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Note that the largest element in the left subtree is still less than the separator.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Likewise, the smallest element in the right subtree is still greater than the separator.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Both of those elements are in leaf nodes, and either one can be the new separator for the two subtrees.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The previous step deleted an element (the new separator) from a leaf node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If that leaf node is now deficient (has fewer than the required number of nodes), then rebalance the tree starting from the leaf node.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Rebalancing starts from a leaf and proceeds toward the root until the tree is balanced.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If deleting an element from a node has brought it under the minimum size, then some elements must be redistributed to bring all nodes up to the minimum.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Usually, the redistribution involves moving an element from a sibling node that has more than the minimum number of nodes.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] That redistribution operation is called a **rotation**.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If no sibling can spare an element, then the deficient node must be **merged** with a sibling.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The merge causes the parent to lose a separator element, so the parent may become deficient and need rebalancing.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The merging and rebalancing may continue all the way to the root.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Since the minimum element count doesn't apply to the root, making the root be the only deficient node is not a problem.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] While freshly loaded databases tend to have good sequential behaviour, this behaviour becomes increasingly difficult to maintain as a database grows, resulting in more random I/O and performance challenges.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A common special case is adding a large amount of *pre-sorted* data into an initially empty B-tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] While it is quite possible to simply perform a series of successive inserts, inserting sorted data results in a tree composed almost entirely of half-full nodes.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Instead, a special "bulk loading" algorithm can be used to produce a more efficient tree with a higher branching factor.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] When the input is sorted, all insertions are at the rightmost edge of the tree, and in particular any time a node is split, we are guaranteed that no more insertions will take place in the left half.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] When bulk loading, we take advantage of this, and instead of splitting overfull nodes evenly, split them as *unevenly* as possible: leave the left node completely full and create a right node with zero keys and one child (in violation of the usual B-tree rules).
[src:data-structures/b-tree] At the end of bulk loading, the tree is composed almost entirely of completely full nodes; only the rightmost node on each level may be less than full.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Because those nodes may also be less than *half* full, to re-establish the normal B-tree rules, combine such nodes with their (guaranteed full) left siblings and divide the keys to produce two nodes at least half full.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The only node which lacks a full left sibling is the root, which is permitted to be less than half full.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In addition to its use in databases, the B-tree (or § Variants) is also used in filesystems to allow quick random access to an arbitrary block in a particular file.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The basic problem is turning the file block i address into a disk block address.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Some early operating systems, and some highly specialized ones, required the application to allocate the maximum size of a file when the file was created.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The file can then be allocated as contiguous disk blocks.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In that case, to convert the file block address i into a disk block address, the operating system simply adds the file block address i to the address of the first disk block constituting the file.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The scheme is simple, but the file cannot exceed its created size.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] All modern, mainstream operating systems allow a file to grow.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The resulting disk blocks may not be contiguous, so mapping logical blocks to physical blocks is more involved.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] MS-DOS, for example, used a simple File Allocation Table (FAT).
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The FAT has an entry for each disk block, and that entry identifies whether its block is used by a file and if so, which block (if any) is the next disk block of the same file.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] So, the allocation of each file is represented as a linked list in the table.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In order to find the disk address of file block i , the operating system (or disk utility) must sequentially follow the file's linked list in the FAT.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Worse, to find a free disk block, it must sequentially scan the FAT.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] For MS-DOS, that was not a huge penalty because the disks and files were small and the FAT had few entries and relatively short file chains.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In the FAT12 filesystem (used on floppy disks and early hard disks), there were no more than 4,080 entries, and the FAT would usually be resident in memory.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] As disks got bigger, the FAT architecture began to confront penalties.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] On a large disk using FAT, it may be necessary to perform disk reads to learn the disk location of a file block to be read or written.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] TOPS-20 used a 0 to 2 level tree that has similarities to a B-tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If the file fit in a 512 (29) word block, then the file directory would point to that physical disk block.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If the file fit in 218 words, then the directory would point to an aux index; the 512 words of that index would either be NULL (the block isn't allocated) or point to the physical address of the block.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] If the file fit in 227 words, then the directory would point to a block holding an aux-aux index; each entry would either be NULL or point to an aux index.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Consequently, the physical disk block for a 227 word file could be located in two disk reads and read on the third.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Apple's filesystem HFS+ and APFS, Microsoft's NTFS, AIX (jfs2) and some Linux filesystems, such as Bcachefs, Btrfs and ext4, use B-trees.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] B*-trees are used in the HFS and Reiser4 file systems.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] DragonFly BSD's HAMMER file system uses a modified B+-tree.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A B-tree grows slower with growing data amount, than the linearity of a linked list.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Compared to a skip list, both structures have the same performance, but the B-tree scales better for growing *n*.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A T-tree, for main memory database systems, is similar but more compact.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Lehman and Yao showed that all the read locks could be avoided (and thus concurrent access greatly improved) by linking the tree blocks at each level together with a "next" pointer.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This results in a tree structure where both insertion and search operations descend from the root to the leaf.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Write locks are only required as a tree block is modified.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] This maximizes access concurrency by multiple users, an important consideration for databases and/or other B-tree-based ISAM storage methods.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The cost associated with this improvement is that empty pages cannot be removed from the btree during normal operations.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] United States Patent 5283894, granted in 1994, appears to show a way to use a 'Meta Access Method' to allow concurrent B+ tree access and modification without locks.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] The technique accesses the tree 'upwards' for both searches and updates by means of additional in-memory indexes that point at the blocks in each level in the block cache.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] No reorganization for deletes is needed and there are no 'next' pointers in each block as in Lehman and Yao.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] Since B-trees are similar in structure to red-black trees, parallel algorithms for red-black trees can be applied to B-trees as well.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] A Maple tree is a B-tree developed for use in the Linux kernel to reduce lock contention in virtual memory management.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] (a,b)-trees are generalizations of B-trees.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] B-trees require that each internal node have a minimum of $\lfloor K/2\rfloor +1$ children and a maximum of K children, for some preset value of K .
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In contrast, an (a,b)-tree allows the minimum number of children for an internal node to be set arbitrarily low.
[src:data-structures/b-tree] In an (a,b)-tree, each internal node has between a and b children, for some preset values of a and b.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **binary search tree** (**BST**), also called an **ordered** or **sorted binary tree**, is a rooted binary tree data structure with the key of each internal node being greater than all the keys in the respective node's left subtree and less than the ones in its right subtree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of operations on the binary search tree is linear with respect to the height of the tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees allow binary search for fast lookup, addition, and removal of data items.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Since the nodes in a BST are laid out so that each comparison skips about half of the remaining tree, the lookup performance is proportional to that of binary logarithm.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] BSTs were devised in the 1960s for the problem of efficient storage of labeled data and are attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The performance of a binary search tree is dependent on the order of insertion of the nodes into the tree since arbitrary insertions may lead to degeneracy; several variations of the binary search tree can be built with guaranteed worst-case performance.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The basic operations include: search, traversal, insert and delete.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] BSTs with guaranteed worst-case complexities perform better than an unsorted array, which would require linear search time.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The complexity analysis of BST shows that, on average, the insert, delete and search takes $\Theta (\log n)$ for n nodes.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] In the worst case, they degrade to that of a singly linked list: $O(n)$ .
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] To address the boundless increase of the tree height with arbitrary insertions and deletions, self-balancing variants of BSTs are introduced to bound the worst lookup complexity to that of the binary logarithm.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] AVL trees were the first self-balancing binary search trees, invented in 1962 by Georgy Adelson-Velsky and Evgenii Landis.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees can be used to implement abstract data types such as dynamic sets, lookup tables and priority queues, and used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The binary search tree algorithm was discovered independently by several researchers, including P.F.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Windley, Andrew Donald Booth, Andrew Colin, Thomas N.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The algorithm is attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler, who used it for storing labeled data in magnetic tapes in 1960.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] One of the earliest and popular binary search tree algorithm is that of Hibbard.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of a binary search tree increases boundlessly with the tree height if the nodes are inserted in an arbitrary order, therefore self-balancing binary search trees were introduced to bound the height of the tree to $O(\log n)$ .
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Various **height-balanced** binary search trees were introduced to confine the tree height, such as AVL trees, Treaps, and red–black trees.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also efficacious in sortings and search algorithms.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also a fundamental data structure used in construction of abstract data structures such as sets, multisets, and associative arrays.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Searching in a binary search tree for a specific key can be programmed recursively or iteratively.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Searching begins by examining the root node.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] If the tree is nil, the key being searched for does not exist in the tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Otherwise, if the key equals that of the root, the search is successful and the node is returned.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] If the key is less than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the left subtree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Similarly, if the key is greater than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the right subtree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] This process is repeated until the key is found or the remaining subtree is ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] If the searched key is not found after a ${\text{nil}}$ subtree is reached, then the key is not present in the tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the BST search procedure through recursion.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The recursive procedure continues until a ${\text{nil}}$ or the ${\text{key}}$ being searched for are encountered.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The recursive version of the search can be "unrolled" into a while loop.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] On most machines, the iterative version is found to be more efficient.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Since the search may proceed till some leaf node, the running time complexity of BST search is $O(h)$ where h is the height of the tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] However, the worst case for BST search is $O(n)$ where n is the total number of nodes in the BST, because an unbalanced BST may degenerate to a linked list.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] However, if the BST is height-balanced the height is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] For certain operations, given a node ${\text{x}}$ , finding the successor or predecessor of ${\text{x}}$ is crucial.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Assuming all the keys of a BST are distinct, the successor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the smallest key greater than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] On the other hand, the predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the largest key smaller than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode finds the successor and predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Operations such as finding a node in a BST whose key is the maximum or minimum are critical in certain operations, such as determining the successor and predecessor of nodes.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Following is the pseudocode for the operations.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Operations such as insertion and deletion cause the BST representation to change dynamically.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The data structure must be modified in such a way that the properties of BST continue to hold.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] New nodes are inserted as leaf nodes in the BST.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Following is an iterative implementation of the insertion operation.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The procedure maintains a "trailing pointer" ${\text{y}}$ as a parent of ${\text{x}}$ .
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] After initialization on line 2, the **while** loop along lines 4-11 causes the pointers to be updated.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{y}}$ is ${\text{nil}}$ , the BST is empty, thus ${\text{z}}$ is inserted as the root node of the binary search tree ${\text{T}}$ , if it is not ${\text{nil}}$ , insertion proceeds by comparing the keys to that of ${\text{y}}$ on the lines 15-19 and the node is inserted accordingly.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{Z}}$ has only one child, the child node of ${\text{Z}}$ gets elevated by modifying the parent node of ${\text{Z}}$ to point to the child node, consequently taking ${\text{Z}}$ 's position in the tree, as shown in (b) and (c).
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{Y}}$ lies within ${\text{Z}}$ 's right subtree but is not ${\text{Z}}$ 's right child, as shown in (e), ${\text{Y}}$ first gets replaced by its own right child, and then it displaces ${\text{Z}}$ 's position in the tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Alternatively, the in-order predecessor can also be used.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the deletion operation in a binary search tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The ${\text{BST-Delete}}$ procedure deals with the 3 special cases mentioned above.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Lines 2-3 deal with case 1; lines 4-5 deal with case 2 and lines 6-16 for case 3.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The helper function ${\text{Shift-Nodes}}$ is used within the deletion algorithm for the purpose of replacing the node ${\text{u}}$ with ${\text{v}}$ in the binary search tree ${\text{BST}}$ .
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] This procedure handles the deletion (and substitution) of ${\text{u}}$ from ${\text{BST}}$ .
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] A BST can be traversed through three basic algorithms: inorder, preorder, and postorder tree walks.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Following is a recursive implementation of the tree walks.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Without rebalancing, insertions or deletions in a binary search tree may lead to degeneration, resulting in a height n of the tree (where n is number of items in a tree), so that the lookup performance is deteriorated to that of a linear search.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Keeping the search tree balanced and height bounded by $O(\log n)$ is a key to the usefulness of the binary search tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] This can be achieved by "self-balancing" mechanisms during the updation operations to the tree designed to maintain the tree height to the binary logarithmic complexity.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] A tree is height-balanced if the heights of the left sub-tree and right sub-tree are guaranteed to be related by a constant factor.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] This property was introduced by the AVL tree and continued by the red–black tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The heights of all the nodes on the path from the root to the modified leaf node have to be observed and possibly corrected on every insert and delete operation to the tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] In a weight-balanced tree, the criterion of a balanced tree is the number of leaves of the subtrees.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The weights of the left and right subtrees differ at most by 1 .
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] However, the difference is bound by a ratio $\alpha$ of the weights, since a strong balance condition of 1 cannot be maintained with $O(\log n)$ rebalancing work during insert and delete operations.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] The $\alpha$ -weight-balanced trees gives an entire family of balance conditions, where each left and right subtrees have each at least a fraction of $\alpha$ of the total weight of the subtree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] There are several self-balanced binary search trees, including T-tree, treap, red-black tree, B-tree, 2–3 tree, and Splay tree.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort, where all the elements are inserted at once and the tree is traversed at an in-order fashion.
[src:data-structures/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in implementing priority queues, using the node's key as priorities.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] In computing, a **Bloom filter** is a space-efficient probabilistic data structure, conceived by Burton Howard Bloom in 1970, that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] False positive matches are possible, but false negatives are not – in other words, a query returns either "possibly in set" or "definitely not in set".
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Elements can be added to the set, but not removed (though this can be addressed with the counting Bloom filter variant); the more items added, the larger the probability of false positives.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Bloom proposed the technique for applications where the amount of source data would require an impractically large amount of memory if "conventional" error-free hashing techniques were applied.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] He gave the example of a hyphenation algorithm for a dictionary of 500,000 words, out of which 90% follow simple hyphenation rules, but the remaining 10% require expensive disk accesses to retrieve specific hyphenation patterns.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] With sufficient core memory, an error-free hash could be used to eliminate all unnecessary disk accesses; on the other hand, with limited core memory, Bloom's technique uses a smaller hash area but still eliminates most unnecessary accesses.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] For example, a hash area only 18% of the size needed by an ideal error-free hash still eliminates 87% of the disk accesses.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] More generally, fewer than 10 bits per element are required for a 1% false positive probability, independent of the size or number of elements in the set.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] An *empty Bloom filter* is a bit array of m bits, all set to 0.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] It is equipped with k different hash functions, which map set elements to one of the m possible array positions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] To be optimal, the hash functions should be uniformly distributed and independent.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Typically, k is a small constant which depends on the desired false error rate ε, while m is proportional to k and the number of elements to be added.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] To *add* an element, feed it to each of the k hash functions to get k array positions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Set the bits at all these positions to 1.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] To *test* whether an element is in the set, feed it to each of the k hash functions to get k array positions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] If *any* of the bits at these positions is 0, the element is definitely not in the set; if it were, then all the bits would have been set to 1 when it was inserted.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] If all are 1, then either the element is in the set, *or* the bits have by chance been set to 1 during the insertion of other elements, resulting in a false positive.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] In a simple Bloom filter, there is no way to distinguish between the two cases, but more advanced techniques can address this problem.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] The requirement of designing k different independent hash functions can be prohibitive for large k.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] For a good hash function with a wide output, there should be little if any correlation between different bit-fields of such a hash, so this type of hash can be used to generate multiple "different" hash functions by slicing its output into multiple bit fields.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Alternatively, one can pass k different initial values (such as 0, 1, ..., k − 1) to a hash function that takes an initial value; or add (or append) these values to the key.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] For larger m and/or k, independence among the hash functions can be relaxed with negligible increase in false positive rate.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Removing an element from this simple Bloom filter is impossible because there is no way to tell which of the k bits it maps to should be cleared.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Although setting any one of those k bits to zero suffices to remove the element, it would also remove any other elements that happen to map onto that bit.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Since the simple algorithm provides no way to determine whether any other elements have been added that affect the bits for the element to be removed, clearing any of the bits would introduce the possibility of false negatives.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] One-time removal of an element from a Bloom filter can be simulated by having a second Bloom filter that contains items that have been removed.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] However, false positives in the second filter become false negatives in the composite filter, which may be undesirable.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] In this approach re-adding a previously removed item is not possible, as one would have to remove it from the "removed" filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] It is often the case that all the keys are available but are expensive to enumerate (for example, requiring many disk reads).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] When the false positive rate gets too high, the filter can be regenerated; this should be a relatively rare event.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] While risking false positives, Bloom filters have a substantial space advantage over other data structures for representing sets, such as self-balancing binary search trees, tries, hash tables, or simple arrays or linked lists of the entries.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Most of these require storing at least the data items themselves, which can require anywhere from a small number of bits, for small integers, to an arbitrary number of bits, such as for strings (tries are an exception since they can share storage between elements with equal prefixes).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] However, Bloom filters do not store the data items at all, and a separate solution must be provided for the actual storage.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Linked structures incur an additional linear space overhead for pointers.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] A Bloom filter with a 1% error and an optimal value of k, in contrast, requires only about 9.6 bits per element, regardless of the size of the elements.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] This advantage comes partly from its compactness, inherited from arrays, and partly from its probabilistic nature.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] The 1% false-positive rate can be reduced by a factor of ten by adding only about 4.8 bits per element.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] However, if the number of potential values is small and many of them can be in the set, the Bloom filter is easily surpassed by the deterministic bit array, which requires only one bit for each potential element.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Hash tables gain a space and time advantage if they begin ignoring collisions and store only whether each bucket contains an entry; in this case, they have effectively become Bloom filters with *k* = 1.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Bloom filters also have the unusual property that the time needed either to add items or to check whether an item is in the set is a fixed constant, O(*k*), completely independent of the number of items already in the set.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] No other constant-space set data structure has this property, but the average access time of sparse hash tables can make them faster in practice than some Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] In a hardware implementation, however, the Bloom filter shines because its k lookups are independent and can be parallelized.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] To understand its space efficiency, it is instructive to compare the general Bloom filter with its special case when *k* = 1.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] If *k* = 1, then in order to keep the false positive rate sufficiently low, a small fraction of bits should be set, which means the array must be very large and contain long runs of zeros.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] The information content of the array relative to its size is low.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Assume that a hash function selects each array position with equal probability.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Now test membership of an element that is not in the set.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Each of the *k* array positions computed by the hash functions is 1 with a probability as above.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] This is not strictly correct as it assumes independence for the probabilities of each bit being set.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] However, assuming it is a close approximation we have that the probability of false positives decreases as *m* (the number of bits in the array) increases, and increases as *n* (the number of inserted elements) increases.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] where the {braces} denote Stirling numbers of the second kind.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] An alternative analysis arriving at the same approximation without the assumption of independence is given by Mitzenmacher and Upfal.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] After all *n* items have been added to the Bloom filter, let *q* be the fraction of the *m* bits that are set to 0.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] (That is, the number of bits still set to 0 is *qm*.) Then, when testing membership of an element not in the set, for the array position given by any of the *k* hash functions, the probability that the bit is found set to 1 is 1 − q {\displaystyle 1-q} ({\displaystyle 1-q}).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] So the probability that all *k* hash functions find their bit set to 1 is ( 1 − q ) k {\displaystyle (1-q)^{k}} ({\displaystyle (1-q)^{k}}).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] It is possible to prove, without the independence assumption, that *q* is very strongly concentrated around its expected value.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] The number of hash functions, *k*, must be a positive integer.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] This means that for a given false positive probability *ε*, the length of a Bloom filter *m* is proportionate to the number of elements being filtered *n* and the required number of hash functions only depends on the target false positive probability *ε*.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Second, of more concern, it assumes that during the membership test the event that one tested bit is set to 1 is independent of the event that any other tested bit is set to 1.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Third, of most concern, it assumes that k = m n ln ⁡ 2 {\displaystyle k={\frac {m}{n}}\ln 2} ({\displaystyle k={\frac {m}{n}}\ln 2}) is fortuitously integral.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Goel and Gupta, however, give a rigorous upper bound that makes no approximations and requires no assumptions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] This bound can be interpreted as saying that the approximate formula ( 1 − e − k n m ) k {\displaystyle \left(1-e^{-{\frac {kn}{m}}}\right)^{k}} ({\displaystyle \left(1-e^{-{\frac {kn}{m}}}\right)^{k}}) can be applied at a penalty of at most half an extra element and at most one less bit.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] where *n ∗ {\displaystyle n^{*}} ({\displaystyle n^{*}})* is an estimate of the number of items in the filter, *m* is the length (size) of the filter, *k* is the number of hash functions, and *X* is the number of bits set to one.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Bloom filters are a way of compactly representing a set of items.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] It is common to try to compute the size of the intersection or union between two sets.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Bloom filters can be used to approximate the size of the intersection and union of two sets.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] where n ( A ∪ B ) {\displaystyle n(A\cup B)} ({\displaystyle n(A\cup B)}) is the number of bits set to one in either of the two Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Classic Bloom filters use 1.44 log 2 ⁡ ( 1 / ε ) {\displaystyle 1.44\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )} ({\displaystyle 1.44\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )}) bits of space per inserted key, where ε {\displaystyle \varepsilon } ({\displaystyle \varepsilon }) is the false positive rate of the Bloom filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] However, the space that is strictly necessary for any data structure playing the same role as a Bloom filter is only log 2 ⁡ ( 1 / ε ) {\displaystyle \log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )} ({\displaystyle \log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )}) per key.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Hence Bloom filters use 44% more space than an equivalent optimal data structure.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Pagh et al. provide a data structure that uses ( 1 + o ( 1 ) ) n log 2 ⁡ ( 1 / ϵ ) + O ( n ) {\textstyle (1+o(1))n\log _{2}(1/\epsilon )+O(n)} ({\textstyle (1+o(1))n\log _{2}(1/\epsilon )+O(n)}) bits while supporting constant amortized expected-time operations.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Advantages of the quotient filter, when compared to the Bloom filter, include its locality of reference and the ability to support deletions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Another alternative to classic Bloom filter is the cuckoo filter, based on space-efficient variants of cuckoo hashing.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] In this case, a hash table is constructed, holding neither keys nor values, but short fingerprints (small hashes) of the keys.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] If looking up the key finds a matching fingerprint, then key is probably in the set.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Cuckoo filters support deletions and have better locality of reference than Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Additionally, in some parameter regimes, cuckoo filters can be parameterized to offer nearly optimal space guarantees.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] This technique, which was first introduced by Carter et al. in 1978, relies on the fact that compact hash tables can be implemented to use roughly n log ⁡ n {\displaystyle n\log n} ({\displaystyle n\log n}) bits less space than their non-compact counterparts.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Using succinct hash tables, the space usage can be reduced to as little as n log 2 ⁡ ( e / ϵ ) + o ( n ) {\displaystyle n\log _{2}(e/\epsilon )+o(n)} ({\displaystyle n\log _{2}(e/\epsilon )+o(n)}) bits while supporting constant-time operations in a wide variety of parameter regimes.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Putze, Sanders & Singler (2007) have studied some variants of Bloom filters that are either faster or use less space than classic Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] The basic idea of the fast variant is to locate the k hash values associated with each key into one or two blocks having the same size as processor's memory cache blocks (usually 64 bytes).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] This will presumably improve performance by reducing the number of potential memory cache misses.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] The proposed variants have however the drawback of using about 32% more space than classic Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] The sequence of values is then sorted and compressed using Golomb coding (or some other compression technique) to occupy a space close to n log 2 ⁡ ( 1 / ε ) {\displaystyle n\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )} ({\displaystyle n\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )}) bits.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] To query the Bloom filter for a given key, it will suffice to check if its corresponding value is stored in the Bloom filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Decompressing the whole Bloom filter for each query would make this variant totally unusable.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] To overcome this problem the sequence of values is divided into small blocks of equal size that are compressed separately.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] At query time only half a block will need to be decompressed on average.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] Because of decompression overhead, this variant may be slower than classic Bloom filters but this may be compensated by the fact that a single hash function needs to be computed.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p01] (The time saving comes from the fact that a lookup requires exactly three memory accesses, which can all execute in parallel.) However, filter creation is more complex than Bloom and cuckoo filters, and it is not possible to modify the set after creation.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] There are over 60 variants of Bloom filters, many surveys of the field, and a continuing churn of applications (see e.g., Luo, *et al* ).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Some of the variants differ sufficiently from the original proposal to be breaches from or forks of the original data structure and its philosophy.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] A treatment which unifies Bloom filters with other work on random projections, compressive sensing, and locality sensitive hashing remains to be done (though see Dasgupta, *et al* for one attempt inspired by neuroscience).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Content delivery networks deploy web caches around the world to cache and serve web content to users with greater performance and reliability.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] A key application of Bloom filters is their use in efficiently determining which web objects to store in these web caches.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Nearly three-quarters of the URLs accessed from a typical web cache are "one-hit-wonders" that are accessed by users only once and never again.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] It is clearly wasteful of disk resources to store one-hit-wonders in a web cache, since they will never be accessed again.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] To prevent caching one-hit-wonders, a Bloom filter is used to keep track of all URLs that are accessed by users.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] A web object is cached only when it has been accessed at least once before, i.e., the object is cached on its second request.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The use of a Bloom filter in this fashion significantly reduces the disk write workload, since most one-hit-wonders are not written to the disk cache.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Further, filtering out the one-hit-wonders also saves cache space on disk, increasing the cache hit rates.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Kiss *et al* described a new construction for the Bloom filter that avoids false positives in addition to the typical non-existence of false negatives.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The construction applies to a finite universe from which set elements are taken.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] It relies on existing non-adaptive combinatorial group testing scheme by Eppstein, Goodrich and Hirschberg.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Unlike the typical Bloom filter, elements are hashed to a bit array through deterministic, fast and simple-to-calculate functions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The maximal set size for which false positives are completely avoided is a function of the universe size and is controlled by the amount of allocated memory.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] As the universe is finite and the set of false positives strictly shrinks with each step, this procedure results in a finite *cascade* of Bloom filters that (on this closed, finite domain) will produce only true positives and true negatives.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] To check for membership in the filter cascade, the initial filter is queried, and, if the result is positive, the second filter is then consulted, and so on.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] This construction is used in CRLite, a proposed certificate revocation status distribution mechanism for the Web PKI, and Certificate Transparency is exploited to close the set of extant certificates.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Counting filters provide a way to implement a *delete* operation on a Bloom filter without recreating the filter afresh.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In a counting filter, the array positions (buckets) are extended from being a single bit to being a multibit counter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In fact, regular Bloom filters can be considered as counting filters with a bucket size of one bit.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Counting filters were introduced by Fan et al.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The insert operation is extended to *increment* the value of the buckets, and the lookup operation checks that each of the required buckets is non-zero.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The delete operation then consists of decrementing the value of each of the respective buckets.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Arithmetic overflow of the buckets is a problem and the buckets should be sufficiently large to make this case rare.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] If it does occur then the increment and decrement operations must leave the bucket set to the maximum possible value in order to retain the properties of a Bloom filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The size of counters is usually 3 or 4 bits.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Hence counting Bloom filters use 3 to 4 times more space than static Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In contrast, the data structures of Pagh, Pagh & Rao (2005) and Fan et al.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] (2014) also allow deletions but use less space than a static Bloom filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Another issue with counting filters is limited scalability.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Because the counting Bloom filter table cannot be expanded, the maximal number of keys to be stored simultaneously in the filter must be known in advance.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Once the designed capacity of the table is exceeded, the false positive rate will grow rapidly as more keys are inserted.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] (2006) introduced a data structure based on d-left hashing that is functionally equivalent but uses approximately half as much space as counting Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The scalability issue does not occur in this data structure.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Once the designed capacity is exceeded, the keys could be reinserted in a new hash table of double size.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The space efficient variant by Putze, Sanders & Singler (2007) could also be used to implement counting filters by supporting insertions and deletions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Rottenstreich, Kanizo & Keslassy (2012) introduced a new general method based on variable increments that significantly improves the false positive probability of counting Bloom filters and their variants, while still supporting deletions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Unlike counting Bloom filters, at each element insertion, the hashed counters are incremented by a hashed variable increment instead of a unit increment.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] To query an element, the exact values of the counters are considered and not just their positiveness.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] If a sum represented by a counter value cannot be composed of the corresponding variable increment for the queried element, a negative answer can be returned to the query.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Bloom filters can be organized in distributed data structures to perform fully decentralized computations of aggregate functions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Decentralized aggregation makes collective measurements locally available in every node of a distributed network without involving a centralized computational entity for this purpose.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Parallel Bloom filters can be implemented to take advantage of the multiple processing elements (PEs) present in parallel shared-nothing machines.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] One of the main obstacles for a parallel Bloom filter is the organization and communication of the unordered data which is, in general, distributed evenly over all PEs at the initiation or at batch insertions.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] To order the data two approaches can be used, either resulting in a Bloom filter over all data being stored on each PE, called replicating bloom filter, or the Bloom filter over all data being split into equal parts, each PE storing one part of it.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] For both approaches a "Single Shot" Bloom filter is used which only calculates one hash, resulting in one flipped bit per element, to reduce the communication volume.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] During the communication of the hashes the PEs search for bits that are set in more than one of the receiving packets, as this would mean that two elements had the same hash and therefore could be duplicates.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] If this occurs a message containing the index of the bit, which is also the hash of the element that could be a duplicate, is sent to the PEs which sent a packet with the set bit.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] If multiple indices are sent to the same PE by one sender it can be advantageous to encode the indices as well.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] All elements that didn't have their hash sent back are now guaranteed to not be a duplicate and won't be evaluated further, for the remaining elements a Repartitioning algorithm can be used.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] First all the elements that had their hash value sent back are sent to the PE that their hash is responsible for.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Any element and its duplicate is now guaranteed to be on the same PE.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In the second step each PE uses a sequential algorithm for duplicate detection on the receiving elements, which are only a fraction of the amount of starting elements.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] By allowing a false positive rate for the duplicates, the communication volume can be reduced further as the PEs don't have to send elements with duplicated hashes at all and instead any element with a duplicated hash can simply be marked as a duplicate.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] As a result, the false positive rate for duplicate detection is the same as the false positive rate of the used bloom filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The process of filtering out the most 'unique' elements can also be repeated multiple times by changing the hash function in each filtering step.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] While using more than two repetitions can reduce the communication volume further if the number of duplicates in a set is small, the payoff for the additional complications is low.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Bloom filters can be used for approximate data synchronization as in Byers et al.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Counting Bloom filters can be used to approximate the number of differences between two sets and this approach is described in Agarwal & Trachtenberg (2006).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Bloom filters can be adapted to the context of streaming data.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Another solution is the Aging Bloom filter, that consists of two Bloom filter each occupying half the total available memory: when one filter is full, the second filter is erased and newer elements are then added to this newly empty filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] This result shows that for L big enough and n going to infinity, then the lower bound converges to F P + F N = 1 {\displaystyle FP+FN=1} ({\displaystyle FP+FN=1}), which is the characteristic relation of a random filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Hence, after enough insertions, and if the alphabet is too big to be stored in memory (which is assumed in the context of probabilistic filters), it is impossible for a filter to perform better than randomness.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] This result can be leveraged by only expecting a filter to operate on a sliding window rather than the whole stream.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In this case, the exponent n in the formula above is replaced by w, which gives a formula that might deviate from 1, if w is not too small.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] (2004) designed a generalization of Bloom filters that could associate a value with each element that had been inserted, implementing an associative array.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Like Bloom filters, these structures achieve a small space overhead by accepting a small probability of false positives.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In the case of "Bloomier filters", a *false positive* is defined as returning a result when the key is not in the map.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The map will never return the wrong value for a key that *is* in the map.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Boldi & Vigna (2005) proposed a lattice-based generalization of Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] A **compact approximator** associates to each key an element of a lattice (the standard Bloom filters being the case of the Boolean two-element lattice).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Instead of a bit array, they have an array of lattice elements.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] When adding a new association between a key and an element of the lattice, they compute the maximum of the current contents of the *k* array locations associated to the key with the lattice element.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] When reading the value associated to a key, they compute the minimum of the values found in the *k* locations associated to the key.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The resulting value approximates from above the original value.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] This implementation used a separate array for each hash function.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] This method allows for parallel hash calculations for both insertions and inquiries.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] (2007) proposed a variant of Bloom filters that can adapt dynamically to the number of elements stored, while assuring a minimum false positive probability.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The technique is based on sequences of standard Bloom filters with increasing capacity and tighter false positive probabilities, so as to ensure that a maximum false positive probability can be set beforehand, regardless of the number of elements to be inserted.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Spatial Bloom filters (SBF) were originally proposed by Palmieri, Calderoni & Maio (2014) as a data structure designed to store location information, especially in the context of cryptographic protocols for location privacy.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] However, the main characteristic of SBFs is their ability to store **multiple sets** in a single data structure, which makes them suitable for a number of different application scenarios.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Membership of an element to a specific set can be queried, and the false positive probability depends on the set: the first sets to be entered into the filter during construction have higher false positive probabilities than sets entered at the end.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] This property allows a prioritization of the sets, where sets containing more "important" elements can be preserved.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] A layered Bloom filter consists of multiple Bloom filter layers.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Layered Bloom filters allow keeping track of how many times an item was added to the Bloom filter by checking how many layers contain the item.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] With a layered Bloom filter a check operation will normally return the deepest layer number the item was found in.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] An attenuated Bloom filter of depth D can be viewed as an array of D normal Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In the context of service discovery in a network, each node stores regular and attenuated Bloom filters locally.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The regular or local Bloom filter indicates which services are offered by the node itself.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The attenuated filter of level i indicates which services can be found on nodes that are i-hops away from the current node.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The i-th value is constructed by taking a union of local Bloom filters for nodes i-hops away from the node.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] For example, consider a small network, shown on the graph below.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Say we are searching for a service A whose id hashes to bits 0,1, and 3 (pattern 11010).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] First, we check whether service A is offered by n1 by checking its local filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Since the patterns don't match, we check the attenuated Bloom filter in order to determine which node should be the next hop.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] We see that n2 doesn't offer service A but lies on the path to nodes that do.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Hence, we move to n2 and repeat the same procedure.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] We quickly find that n3 offers the service, and hence the destination is located.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] By using attenuated Bloom filters consisting of multiple layers, services at more than one hop distance can be discovered while avoiding saturation of the Bloom filter by attenuating (shifting out) bits set by sources further away.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Bloom filters are often used to search large chemical structure databases (see chemical similarity).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In the simplest case, the elements added to the filter (called a *fingerprint* in this field) are just the atomic numbers present in the molecule, or a hash based on the atomic number of each atom and the number and type of its bonds.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] More advanced filters also encode atom counts, larger substructure features like carboxyl groups, and graph properties like the number of rings.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In hash-based fingerprints, a hash function based on atom and bond properties is used to turn a subgraph into a PRNG seed, and the first output values used to set bits in the Bloom filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Molecular fingerprints started in the late 1940s as way to search for chemical structures searched on punched cards.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] However, it wasn't until around 1990 that Daylight Chemical Information Systems, Inc. introduced a hash-based method to generate the bits, rather than use a precomputed table.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Unlike the dictionary approach, the hash method can assign bits for substructures which hadn't previously been seen.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] In the early 1990s, the term "fingerprint" was considered different from "structural keys", but the term has since grown to encompass most molecular characteristics which can be used for a similarity comparison, including structural keys, sparse count fingerprints, and 3D fingerprints.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Unlike Bloom filters, the Daylight hash method allows the number of bits assigned per feature to be a function of the feature size, but most implementations of Daylight-like fingerprints use a fixed number of bits per feature, which makes them a Bloom filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] The original Daylight fingerprints could be used for both similarity and screening purposes.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Many other fingerprint types, like the popular ECFP2, can be used for similarity but not for screening because they include local environmental characteristics that introduce false negatives when used as a screen.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter-p02] Even if these are constructed with the same mechanism, these are not Bloom filters because they cannot be used to filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] (That is, the number of bits still set to 0 is *qm*.) Then, when testing membership of an element not in the set, for the array position given by any of the *k* hash functions, the probability that the bit is found set to 1 is $1-q$ .
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] So the probability that all *k* hash functions find their bit set to 1 is $(1-q)^{k}$ .
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] The formula $m=-{\frac {n\ln \varepsilon }{(\ln 2)^{2}}}$ is approximate for three reasons.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] First, and of least concern, it approximates $1-{\frac {1}{m}}$ as $e^{-{\frac {1}{m}}}$ , which is a good asymptotic approximation (i.e., which holds as *m* →∞).
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] Third, of most concern, it assumes that $k={\frac {m}{n}}\ln 2$ is fortuitously integral.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] This bound can be interpreted as saying that the approximate formula $\left(1-e^{-{\frac {kn}{m}}}\right)^{k}$ can be applied at a penalty of at most half an extra element and at most one less bit.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] where *$n^{*}$* is an estimate of the number of items in the filter, *m* is the length (size) of the filter, *k* is the number of hash functions, and *X* is the number of bits set to one.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] where $n(A\cup B)$ is the number of bits set to one in either of the two Bloom filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] Classic Bloom filters use $1.44\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )$ bits of space per inserted key, where $\varepsilon$ is the false positive rate of the Bloom filter.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] However, the space that is strictly necessary for any data structure playing the same role as a Bloom filter is only $\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )$ per key.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] Pagh et al. provide a data structure that uses ${\textstyle (1+o(1))n\log _{2}(1/\epsilon )+O(n)}$ bits while supporting constant amortized expected-time operations.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] Their data structure is primarily theoretical, but it is closely related to the widely-used quotient filter, which can be parameterized to use $(1+\delta )n\log \epsilon ^{-1}+3n$ bits of space, for an arbitrary parameter $\delta >0$ , while supporting $O(\delta ^{-2})$ -time operations.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] Many alternatives to Bloom filters, including quotient filters and cuckoo filters, are based on the idea of hashing keys to random $(\log n+\log \epsilon ^{-1})$ -bit fingerprints, and then storing those fingerprints in a compact hash table.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] This technique, which was first introduced by Carter et al. in 1978, relies on the fact that compact hash tables can be implemented to use roughly $n\log n$ bits less space than their non-compact counterparts.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] Using succinct hash tables, the space usage can be reduced to as little as $n\log _{2}(e/\epsilon )+o(n)$ bits while supporting constant-time operations in a wide variety of parameter regimes.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] The space efficient variant relies on using a single hash function that generates for each key a value in the range $\left[0,n/\varepsilon \right]$ where $\varepsilon$ is the requested false positive rate.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] The sequence of values is then sorted and compressed using Golomb coding (or some other compression technique) to occupy a space close to $n\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )$ bits.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] Graf & Lemire (2020) describes an approach called an *xor filter*, where they store fingerprints in a particular type of perfect hash table, producing a filter which is more memory efficient ( $1.23\log _{2}(1/\varepsilon )$ bits per key) and faster than Bloom or cuckoo filters.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] (2019) shows that false positive of Counting Bloom filter decreases from k=1 to a point defined $k_{opt}$ , and increases from $k_{opt}$ to positive infinity, and finds $k_{opt}$ as a function of count threshold.
[src:data-structures/bloom-filter] This result shows that for L big enough and n going to infinity, then the lower bound converges to $FP+FN=1$ , which is the characteristic relation of a random filter.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a **graph** is an abstract data type that is meant to implement the undirected graph and directed graph concepts from the field of graph theory within mathematics.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure consists of a finite (and possibly mutable) set of *vertices* (also called *nodes* or *points*), together with a set of unordered pairs of these vertices for an undirected graph or a set of ordered pairs for a directed graph.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] These pairs are known as *edges* (also called *links* or *lines*), and for a directed graph are also known as *edges* but also sometimes *arrows* or *arcs*.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertices may be part of the graph structure, or may be external entities represented by integer indices or references.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure may also associate to each edge some *edge value*, such as a symbolic label or a numeric attribute (cost, capacity, length, etc.).
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] This data structure allows the storage of additional data on the vertices.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Additional data can be stored if edges are also stored as objects, in which case each vertex stores its incident edges and each edge stores its incident vertices.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent source vertices and columns represent destination vertices.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Data on edges and vertices must be stored externally.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Only the cost for one edge can be stored between each pair of vertices.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent the vertices and columns represent the edges.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] The entries indicate the incidence relation between the vertex at a row and edge at a column.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] The following table gives the time complexity cost of performing various operations on graphs, for each of these representations, with |*V*| the number of vertices and |*E*| the number of edges.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] In the matrix representations, the entries encode the cost of following an edge.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] The cost of edges that are not present are assumed to be ∞.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] A representation of adjacent vertices via hash tables leads to an amortized average time complexity of $O(1)$ to test adjacency of two given vertices and to remove an edge and an amortized average time complexity of $O(\deg(x))$ to remove a given vertex x of degree $\deg(x)$ .
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] The time complexity of the other operations and the asymptotic space requirement do not change.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] The parallelization of graph problems faces significant challenges: Data-driven computations, unstructured problems, poor locality and high data access to computation ratio.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] The graph representation used for parallel architectures plays a significant role in facing those challenges.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Poorly chosen representations may unnecessarily drive up the communication cost of the algorithm, which will decrease its scalability.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] In the following, shared and distributed memory architectures are considered.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] In the case of a shared memory model, the graph representations used for parallel processing are the same as in the sequential case, since parallel read-only access to the graph representation (e.g. an adjacency list) is efficient in shared memory.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] In the distributed memory model, the usual approach is to partition the vertex set V of the graph into p sets $V_{0},\dots ,V_{p-1}$ .
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Here, p is the amount of available processing elements (PE).
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertex set partitions are then distributed to the PEs with matching index, additionally to the corresponding edges.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Every PE has its own subgraph representation, where edges with an endpoint in another partition require special attention.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] For standard communication interfaces like MPI, the ID of the PE owning the other endpoint has to be identifiable.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] During computation in a distributed graph algorithms, passing information along these edges implies communication.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Partitioning the graph needs to be done carefully - there is a trade-off between low communication and even size partitioning But partitioning a graph is a NP-hard problem, so it is not feasible to calculate them.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Instead, the following heuristics are used.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] 1D partitioning: Every processor gets $n/p$ vertices and the corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be understood as a row-wise or column-wise decomposition of the adjacency matrix.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] For algorithms operating on this representation, this requires an All-to-All communication step as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ message buffer sizes, as each PE potentially has outgoing edges to every other PE.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] 2D partitioning: Every processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Assume the processors are aligned in a rectangle $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ , where $p_{r}$ and $p_{c}$ are the amount of processing elements in each row and column, respectively.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Then each processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix of dimension $(n/p_{r})\times (n/p_{c})$ .
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be visualized as a checkerboard pattern in a matrix.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Therefore, each processing unit can only have outgoing edges to PEs in the same row and column.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] This bounds the amount of communication partners for each PE to $p_{r}+p_{c}-1$ out of $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ possible ones.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Graphs with trillions of edges occur in machine learning, social network analysis, and other areas.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Compressed graph representations have been developed to reduce I/O and memory requirements.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] General techniques such as Huffman coding are applicable, but the adjacency list or adjacency matrix can be processed in specific ways to increase efficiency.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Breadth-first search (BFS) and depth-first search (DFS) are two closely related approaches that are used for exploring all of the nodes in a given connected component.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Both start with an arbitrary node, the "root".
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Strongly connected components can also be found using graph traversals using algorithms such as Kosaraju's algorithm, which is a modified DFS.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] Dijkstra's Algorithm is a Pathfinding Algorithm that can be used on a positively-weighted (meaning all edge weights must be greater than or equal to 0) and/or directed graphs.
[src:data-structures/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be used to find the shortest path between two arbitrarily chosen nodes which is commonly applied in routing problems.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] In computer science, a **heap** is a tree-based data structure that satisfies the **heap property**: In a *max heap*, for any given node C, if P is the parent node of C, then the *key* (the *value*) of P is greater than or equal to the key of C.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] In a *min heap*, the key of P is less than or equal to the key of C.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The node at the "top" of the heap (with no parents) is called the *root* node.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The heap is one maximally efficient implementation of an abstract data type called a priority queue, and in fact, priority queues are often referred to as "heaps", regardless of how they may be implemented.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] In a heap, the highest (or lowest) priority element is always stored at the root.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] However, a heap is not a sorted structure; it can be regarded as being partially ordered.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] A heap is a useful data structure when it is necessary to repeatedly remove the object with the highest (or lowest) priority, or when insertions need to be interspersed with removals of the root node.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] A common implementation of a heap is the binary heap, in which the tree is a complete binary tree (see figure).
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure, specifically the binary heap, was introduced by J.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Williams in 1964, as a data structure for the heapsort sorting algorithm.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Heaps are also crucial in several efficient graph algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] When a heap is a complete binary tree, it has the smallest possible height—a heap with *N* nodes and *a* branches for each node always has log*a* *N* height.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Note that, as shown in the graphic, there is no implied ordering between siblings or cousins and no implied sequence for an in-order traversal (as there would be in, e.g., a binary search tree).
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The heap relation mentioned above applies only between nodes and their parents, grandparents.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The maximum number of children each node can have depends on the type of heap.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Heaps are typically constructed in-place in the same array where the elements are stored, with their structure being implicit in the access pattern of the operations.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Heaps differ in this way from other data structures with similar or in some cases better theoretic bounds such as radix trees in that they require no additional memory beyond that used for storing the keys.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] For a binary heap, in the array, the first index contains the root element.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The next two indices of the array contain the root's children.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The next four indices contain the four children of the root's two child nodes, and so on.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Therefore, given a node at index i, its children are at indices ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $2i+2$ ⁠, and its parent is at index ⌊(*i*−1)/2⌋ in an array starting from index ⁠ 0 ⁠, or at ⁠ $2i$ ⁠, ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠, and ⌊*i*/2⌋, respectively, in an array starting from ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] This simple indexing scheme makes it efficient to walk "up" or "down" the tree.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Balancing a heap is done by sift-up or sift-down operations (swapping elements which are out of order).
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] As we can build a heap from an array without requiring extra memory (for the nodes, for example), heapsort can be used to sort an array in-place.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] After an element is inserted into or deleted from a heap, the heap property may be violated, and the heap must be re-balanced by swapping elements within the array.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] This is faster than a sequence of consecutive insertions into an originally empty heap, which is log-linear.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] *make-heap* is the operation of building a heap from a sequence of *n* unsorted elements.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] It can be done in *Θ*(*n*) time whenever *meld* runs in *O*(log *n*) time (where both complexities can be amortized).
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Another algorithm achieves *Θ*(*n*) for binary heaps.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] For persistent heaps (not supporting *increase-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-max* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-max* and *meld*.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-max* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *increase-key* is not supported.
[src:data-structures/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure has many applications.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In computer science, a **linked list** is a linear collection of data elements whose order is not given by their physical placement in memory.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Instead, each element points to the next.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] It is a data structure consisting of a collection of nodes which together represent a sequence.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In its most basic form, each node contains data, and a reference (in other words, a *link*) to the next node in the sequence.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This structure allows for efficient insertion or removal of elements from any position in the sequence during iteration.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] More complex variants add additional links, allowing more efficient insertion or removal of nodes at arbitrary positions.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A drawback of linked lists is that data access time is linear with respect to the number of nodes in the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Because nodes are serially linked, accessing any node requires that the prior node be accessed beforehand (which introduces difficulties in pipelining).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Faster access, such as random access, is not feasible.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Arrays have better cache locality compared to linked lists.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Linked lists are among the simplest and most common data structures.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] They can be used to implement several other common abstract data types, including lists, stacks, queues, associative arrays, and S-expressions, though it is not uncommon to implement those data structures directly without using a linked list as the basis.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In an array, the data is stored in memory is in contiguous fashion i.e. the data is stored to very next idle memory location to previous one.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] But in Linked list data is not stored in contiguous memory locations, instead the node holding the reference to other node's memory address is in sequential order.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Linked lists allow insertion and removal of nodes at any point in the list, and allow doing so with a constant number of operations by keeping the link previous to the link being added or removed in memory during list traversal.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This practice resurfaced during the early years of mechanical printing of books in Europe, when it was common practice for printers to include at the end of each printed page a "catchword" corresponding to the first word on the page next in order.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The first implementation of linked listing in the computer-science context was developed in 1955–1956 by Allen Newell, Cliff Shaw, and Herbert A.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Simon at RAND Corporation and Carnegie Mellon University as the primary data structure for their Information Processing Language (IPL).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] IPL was used by the authors to develop several early artificial intelligence programs, including the Logic Theory Machine, the General Problem Solver, and a computer chess program.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The now-classic diagram consisting of blocks representing list nodes with arrows pointing to successive list nodes appears in "Programming the Logic Theory Machine" by Newell and Shaw in Proc.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Newell and Simon were recognized with the ACM Turing Award in 1975 for having "made basic contributions to artificial intelligence, the psychology of human cognition, and list processing".
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The problem of machine translation for natural language processing led Victor Yngve at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) to use linked lists as data structures in his COMIT programming language for computer research in the field of linguistics.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A report on this language entitled "A programming language for mechanical translation" appeared in Mechanical Translation in 1958.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Another early appearance of linked lists was by Hans Peter Luhn who wrote an internal IBM memorandum in January 1953 that suggested the use of linked lists in chained hash tables.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] LISP, standing for list processor, was created by John McCarthy in 1958 while he was at MIT and in 1960 he published its design in a paper in the Communications of the ACM, entitled "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I".
[src:data-structures/linked-list] One of LISP's major data structures is the linked list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] By the early 1960s, the utility of both linked lists and languages which use these structures as their primary data representation was well established.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Bert Green of the MIT Lincoln Laboratory published a review article entitled "Computer languages for symbol manipulation" in IRE Transactions on Human Factors in Electronics in March 1961 which summarized the advantages of the linked list approach.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A later review article, "A Comparison of list-processing computer languages" by Bobrow and Raphael, appeared in Communications of the ACM in April 1964.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Several operating systems developed by Technical Systems Consultants (originally of West Lafayette Indiana, and later of Chapel Hill, North Carolina) used singly linked lists as file structures.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A directory entry pointed to the first sector of a file, and succeeding portions of the file were located by traversing pointers.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Systems using this technique included Flex (for the Motorola 6800 CPU), mini-Flex (same CPU), and Flex9 (for the Motorola 6809 CPU).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A variant developed by TSC for and marketed by Smoke Signal Broadcasting in California, used doubly linked lists in the same manner.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The TSS/360 operating system, developed by IBM for the System 360/370 machines, used a double linked list for their file system catalog.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The directory structure was similar to Unix, where a directory could contain files and other directories and extend to any depth.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Each record of a linked list is often called an 'element' or 'node'.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The field of each node that contains the address of the next node is usually called the 'next link' or 'next pointer'.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The remaining fields are known as the 'data', 'information', 'value', 'cargo', or 'payload' fields.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The 'tail' of a list may refer either to the rest of the list after the head, or to the last node in the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In Lisp and some derived languages, the next node may be called the 'cdr' (pronounced /'kʊd.əɹ/) of the list, while the payload of the head node may be called the 'car'.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Singly linked lists contain nodes which have a 'value' field as well as 'next' field, which points to the next node in line of nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Operations that can be performed on singly linked lists include insertion, deletion and traversal.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In a 'doubly linked list', each node contains, besides the link to the next node, a second link field pointing to the 'previous' node in the sequence.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The two links may be called 'forward('s') and 'backwards', or 'next' and 'prev'('previous').
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A technique known as XOR-linking allows a doubly linked list to be implemented using a single link field in each node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] However, this technique requires the ability to do bit operations on addresses, and therefore may not be available in some high-level languages.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Many modern operating systems use doubly linked lists to maintain references to active processes, threads, and other dynamic objects.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A common strategy for rootkits to evade detection is to unlink themselves from these lists.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In a 'multiply linked list', each node contains two or more link fields, each field being used to connect the same set of data arranged in a different order (e.g., by name, by department, by date of birth, etc.).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] While a doubly linked list can be seen as a special case of multiply linked list, the fact that the two and more orders are opposite to each other leads to simpler and more efficient algorithms, so they are usually treated as a separate case.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In the last node of a linked list, the link field often contains a null reference, a special value used to indicate the lack of further nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A less common convention is to make it point to the first node of the list; in that case, the list is said to be 'circular' or 'circularly linked'; otherwise, it is said to be 'open' or 'linear'.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] It is a list where the last node pointer points to the first node (i.e., the "link to next node" pointer of the last node has the memory address of the first node).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In the case of a circular doubly linked list, the first node also points to the last node of the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In some implementations an extra 'sentinel' or 'dummy' node may be added before the first data record or after the last one.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This convention simplifies and accelerates some list-handling algorithms, by ensuring that all links can be safely dereferenced and that every list (even one that contains no data elements) always has a "first" and "last" node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] An empty list is a list that contains no data records.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This is usually the same as saying that it has zero nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] If sentinel nodes are being used, the list is usually said to be empty when it has only sentinel nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The link fields need not be physically part of the nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] If the data records are stored in an array and referenced by their indices, the link field may be stored in a separate array with the same indices as the data records.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Since a reference to the first node gives access to the whole list, that reference is often called the 'address', 'pointer', or 'handle' of the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Algorithms that manipulate linked lists usually get such handles to the input lists and return the handles to the resulting lists.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In fact, in the context of such algorithms, the word "list" often means "list handle".
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In some situations, however, it may be convenient to refer to a list by a handle that consists of two links, pointing to its first and last nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The alternatives listed above may be arbitrarily combined in almost every way, so one may have circular doubly linked lists without sentinels, circular singly linked lists with sentinels, etc.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] As with most choices in computer programming and design, no method is well suited to all circumstances.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A linked list data structure might work well in one case, but cause problems in another.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This is a list of some of the common tradeoffs involving linked list structures.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A *dynamic array* is a data structure that allocates all elements contiguously in memory, and keeps a count of the current number of elements.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] If the space reserved for the dynamic array is exceeded, it is reallocated and (possibly) copied, which is an expensive operation.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Linked lists have several advantages over dynamic arrays.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] While one can "delete" an element from an array in constant time by somehow marking its slot as "vacant", this causes fragmentation that impedes the performance of iteration.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This helps with appending elements at the array's end, but inserting into (or removing from) middle positions still carries prohibitive costs due to data moving to maintain contiguity.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] An array from which many elements are removed may also have to be resized in order to avoid wasting too much space.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] On the other hand, dynamic arrays (as well as fixed-size array data structures) allow constant-time random access, while linked lists allow only sequential access to elements.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Singly linked lists, in fact, can be easily traversed in only one direction.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This makes linked lists unsuitable for applications where it's useful to look up an element by its index quickly, such as heapsort.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Sequential access on arrays and dynamic arrays is also faster than on linked lists on many machines, because they have optimal locality of reference and thus make good use of data caching.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Another disadvantage of linked lists is the extra storage needed for references, which often makes them impractical for lists of small data items such as characters or Boolean values, because the storage overhead for the links may exceed by a factor of two or more the size of the data.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In contrast, a dynamic array requires only the space for the data itself (and a very small amount of control data).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] It can also be slow, and with a naïve allocator, wasteful, to allocate memory separately for each new element, a problem generally solved using memory pools.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Some hybrid solutions try to combine the advantages of the two representations.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Unrolled linked lists store several elements in each list node, increasing cache performance while decreasing memory overhead for references.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] CDR coding does both these as well, by replacing references with the actual data referenced, which extends off the end of the referencing record.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A good example that highlights the pros and cons of using dynamic arrays vs. linked lists is by implementing a program that resolves the Josephus problem.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The Josephus problem is an election method that works by having a group of people stand in a circle.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Starting at a predetermined person, one may count around the circle *n* times.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Once the *n*th person is reached, one should remove them from the circle and have the members close the circle.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The process is repeated until only one person is left.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This shows the strengths and weaknesses of a linked list vs. a dynamic array, because if the people are viewed as connected nodes in a circular linked list, then it shows how easily the linked list is able to delete nodes (as it only has to rearrange the links to the different nodes).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] However, the linked list will be poor at finding the next person to remove and will need to search through the list until it finds that person.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A dynamic array, on the other hand, will be poor at deleting nodes (or elements) as it cannot remove one node without individually shifting all the elements up the list by one.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] However, it is exceptionally easy to find the *n*th person in the circle by directly referencing them by their position in the array.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The list ranking problem concerns the efficient conversion of a linked list representation into an array.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Although trivial for a conventional computer, solving this problem by a parallel algorithm is complicated and has been the subject of much research.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A balanced tree has similar memory access patterns and space overhead to a linked list while permitting much more efficient indexing, taking O(log n) time instead of O(n) for a random access.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] However, insertion and deletion operations are more expensive due to the overhead of tree manipulations to maintain balance.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Schemes exist for trees to automatically maintain themselves in a balanced state: AVL trees or red–black trees.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] While doubly linked and circular lists have advantages over singly linked linear lists, linear lists offer some advantages that make them preferable in some situations.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A singly linked linear list is a recursive data structure, because it contains a pointer to a *smaller* object of the same type.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] For that reason, many operations on singly linked linear lists (such as merging two lists, or enumerating the elements in reverse order) often have very simple recursive algorithms, much simpler than any solution using iterative commands.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] While those recursive solutions can be adapted for doubly linked and circularly linked lists, the procedures generally need extra arguments and more complicated base cases.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Linear singly linked lists also allow tail-sharing, the use of a common final portion of sub-list as the terminal portion of two different lists.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In particular, if a new node is added at the beginning of a list, the former list remains available as the tail of the new one—a simple example of a persistent data structure.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Again, this is not true with the other variants: a node may never belong to two different circular or doubly linked lists.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In particular, end-sentinel nodes can be shared among singly linked non-circular lists.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The same end-sentinel node may be used for *every* such list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In Lisp, for example, every proper list ends with a link to a special node, denoted by `nil` or `()`.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The advantages of the fancy variants are often limited to the complexity of the algorithms, not in their efficiency.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A circular list, in particular, can usually be emulated by a linear list together with two variables that point to the first and last nodes, at no extra cost.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Double-linked lists require more space per node (unless one uses XOR-linking), and their elementary operations are more expensive; but they are often easier to manipulate because they allow fast and easy sequential access to the list in both directions.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In a doubly linked list, one can insert or delete a node in a constant number of operations given only that node's address.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] To do the same in a singly linked list, one must have the *address of the pointer* to that node, which is either the handle for the whole list (in case of the first node) or the link field in the *previous* node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Some algorithms require access in both directions.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] On the other hand, doubly linked lists do not allow tail-sharing and cannot be used as persistent data structures.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A circularly linked list may be a natural option to represent arrays that are naturally circular, e.g. the corners of a polygon, a pool of buffers that are used and released in FIFO ("first in, first out") order, or a set of processes that should be time-shared in round-robin order.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In these applications, a pointer to any node serves as a handle to the whole list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] With a circular list, a pointer to the last node gives easy access also to the first node, by following one link.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Thus, in applications that require access to both ends of the list (e.g., in the implementation of a queue), a circular structure allows one to handle the structure by a single pointer, instead of two.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A circular list can be split into two circular lists, in constant time, by giving the addresses of the last node of each piece.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The operation consists in swapping the contents of the link fields of those two nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Applying the same operation to any two nodes in two distinct lists joins the two list into one.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This property greatly simplifies some algorithms and data structures, such as the quad-edge and face-edge.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The simplest representation for an empty *circular* list (when such a thing makes sense) is a null pointer, indicating that the list has no nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Without this choice, many algorithms have to test for this special case, and handle it separately.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] By contrast, the use of null to denote an empty *linear* list is more natural and often creates fewer special cases.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] For some applications, it can be useful to use singly linked lists that can vary between being circular and being linear, or even circular with a linear initial segment.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Algorithms for searching or otherwise operating on these have to take precautions to avoid accidentally entering an endless loop.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] One well-known method is to have a second pointer walking the list at half or double the speed, and if both pointers meet at the same node, a cycle has been found.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Sentinel node may simplify certain list operations, by ensuring that the next or previous nodes exist for every element, and that even empty lists have at least one node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] One may also use a sentinel node at the end of the list, with an appropriate data field, to eliminate some end-of-list tests.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] For example, when scanning the list looking for a node with a given value *x*, setting the sentinel's data field to *x* makes it unnecessary to test for end-of-list inside the loop.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Another example is the merging two sorted lists: if their sentinels have data fields set to +∞, the choice of the next output node does not need special handling for empty lists.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] However, sentinel nodes use up extra space (especially in applications that use many short lists), and they may complicate other operations (such as the creation of a new empty list).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] However, if the circular list is used merely to simulate a linear list, one may avoid some of this complexity by adding a single sentinel node to every list, between the last and the first data nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] With this convention, an empty list consists of the sentinel node alone, pointing to itself via the next-node link.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The list handle should then be a pointer to the last data node, before the sentinel, if the list is not empty; or to the sentinel itself, if the list is empty.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The same trick can be used to simplify the handling of a doubly linked linear list, by turning it into a circular doubly linked list with a single sentinel node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] However, in this case, the handle should be a single pointer to the dummy node itself.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] When manipulating linked lists in-place, care must be taken to not use values that have been invalidated in previous assignments.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This makes algorithms for inserting or deleting linked list nodes somewhat subtle.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This section gives pseudocode for adding or removing nodes from singly, doubly, and circularly linked lists in-place.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Throughout, *null* is used to refer to an end-of-list marker or sentinel, which may be implemented in a number of ways.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The node data structure will have two fields.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] There is also a variable, *firstNode* which always points to the first node in the list, or is *null* for an empty list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The following code inserts a node after an existing node in a singly linked list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Inserting a node before an existing one cannot be done directly; instead, one must keep track of the previous node and insert a node after it.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Inserting at the beginning of the list requires a separate function.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Similarly, there are functions for removing the node *after* a given node, and for removing a node from the beginning of the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] To find and remove a particular node, one must again keep track of the previous element.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Notice that `removeBeginning()` sets `list.firstNode` to `null` when removing the last node in the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Since it is not possible to iterate backwards, efficient `insertBefore` or `removeBefore` operations are not possible.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Inserting to a list before a specific node requires traversing the list, which would have a worst case running time of O(n).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Appending one linked list to another can be inefficient unless a reference to the tail is kept as part of the List structure, because it is needed to traverse the entire first list in order to find the tail, and then append the second list to this.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Thus, if two linearly linked lists are each of length n , list appending has asymptotic time complexity of $O(n)$ .
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In the Lisp family of languages, list appending is provided by the `append` procedure.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Many of the special cases of linked list operations can be eliminated by including a dummy element at the front of the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This ensures that there are no special cases for the beginning of the list and renders both `insertBeginning()` and `removeBeginning()` unnecessary, i.e., every element or node is next to another node (even the first node is next to the dummy node).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In this case, the first useful data in the list will be found at `list.**firstNode**.next`.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In a circularly linked list, all nodes are linked in a continuous circle, without using *null.* For lists with a front and a back (such as a queue), one stores a reference to the last node in the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The *next* node after the last node is the first node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Elements can be added to the back of the list and removed from the front in constant time.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Circularly linked lists can be either singly or doubly linked.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Both types of circularly linked lists benefit from the ability to traverse the full list beginning at any given node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This often allows us to avoid storing *firstNode* and *lastNode*, although if the list may be empty, there needs to be a special representation for the empty list, such as a *lastNode* variable which points to some node in the list or is *null* if it is empty; it uses such a *lastNode* here.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This representation significantly simplifies adding and removing nodes with a non-empty list, but empty lists are then a special case.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Notice that the test "**while** node ≠ someNode" must be at the end of the loop.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] If the test was moved to the beginning of the loop, the procedure would fail whenever the list had only one node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This function inserts a node "newNode" into a circular linked list after a given node "node".
[src:data-structures/linked-list] If "node" is null, it assumes that the list is empty.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Suppose that "L" is a variable pointing to the last node of a circular linked list (or null if the list is empty).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This function inserts a value "newVal" before a given node "node" in O(1) time.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A new node has been created between "node" and the next node, then puts the value of "node" into that new node, and puts "newVal" in "node".
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Thus, a singly linked circularly linked list with only a *firstNode* variable can both insert to the front and back in O(1) time.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This function removes a non-null node from a list of size greater than 1 in O(1) time.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] It copies data from the next node into the node, and then sets the node's *next* pointer to skip over the next node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Languages that do not support any type of reference can still create links by replacing pointers with array indices.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The approach is to keep an array of records, where each record has integer fields indicating the index of the next (and possibly previous) node in the array.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Not all nodes in the array need be used.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] If records are also not supported, parallel arrays can often be used instead.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A linked list can be built by creating an array of these structures, and an integer variable to store the index of the first element.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Links between elements are formed by placing the array index of the next (or previous) cell into the Next or Prev field within a given element.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In the above example, `ListHead` would be set to 2, the location of the first entry in the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Notice that entry 3 and 5 through 7 are not part of the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] These cells are available for any additions to the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] By creating a `ListFree` integer variable, a free list could be created to keep track of what cells are available.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] If all entries are in use, the size of the array would have to be increased or some elements would have to be deleted before new entries could be stored in the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This approach has one main disadvantage, however: it creates and manages a private memory space for its nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] For these reasons, this approach is mainly used for languages that do not support dynamic memory allocation.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] These disadvantages are also mitigated if the maximum size of the list is known at the time the array is created.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Many programming languages such as Lisp and Scheme have singly linked lists built in.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In many functional languages, these lists are constructed from nodes, each called a *cons* or *cons cell*.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The cons has two fields: the *car*, a reference to the data for that node, and the *cdr*, a reference to the next node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Although cons cells can be used to build other data structures, this is their primary purpose.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In languages that support abstract data types or templates, linked list ADTs or templates are available for building linked lists.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In other languages, linked lists are typically built using references together with records.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] When constructing a linked list, one is faced with the choice of whether to store the data of the list directly in the linked list nodes, called *internal storage*, or merely to store a reference to the data, called *external storage*.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Internal storage has the advantage of making access to the data more efficient, requiring less storage overall, having better locality of reference, and simplifying memory management for the list (its data is allocated and deallocated at the same time as the list nodes).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] External storage, on the other hand, has the advantage of being more generic, in that the same data structure and machine code can be used for a linked list no matter what the size of the data is.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] It also makes it easy to place the same data in multiple linked lists.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Although with internal storage the same data can be placed in multiple lists by including multiple *next* references in the node data structure, it would then be necessary to create separate routines to add or delete cells based on each field.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] It is possible to create additional linked lists of elements that use internal storage by using external storage, and having the cells of the additional linked lists store references to the nodes of the linked list containing the data.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In general, if a set of data structures needs to be included in linked lists, external storage is the best approach.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] If a set of data structures need to be included in only one linked list, then internal storage is slightly better, unless a generic linked list package using external storage is available.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Likewise, if different sets of data that can be stored in the same data structure are to be included in a single linked list, then internal storage would be fine.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Another approach that can be used with some languages involves having different data structures, but all have the initial fields, including the *next* (and *prev* if double linked list) references in the same location.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] After defining separate structures for each type of data, a generic structure can be defined that contains the minimum amount of data shared by all the other structures and contained at the top (beginning) of the structures.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Then generic routines can be created that use the minimal structure to perform linked list type operations, but separate routines can then handle the specific data.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This approach is often used in message parsing routines, where several types of messages are received, but all start with the same set of fields, usually including a field for message type.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The generic routines are used to add new messages to a queue when they are received, and remove them from the queue in order to process the message.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The message type field is then used to call the correct routine to process the specific type of message.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Notice that when using external storage, an extra step is needed to extract the record from the node and cast it into the proper data type.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This is because both the list of families and the list of members within the family are stored in two linked lists using the same data structure (*node*), and this language does not have parametric types.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] As long as the number of families that a member can belong to is known at compile time, internal storage works fine.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] If, however, a member needed to be included in an arbitrary number of families, with the specific number known only at run time, external storage would be necessary.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Finding a specific element in a linked list, even if it is sorted, normally requires O(*n*) time (linear search).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This is one of the primary disadvantages of linked lists over other data structures.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In addition to the variants discussed above, below are two simple ways to improve search time.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] In an unordered list, one simple heuristic for decreasing average search time is the *move-to-front heuristic*, which simply moves an element to the beginning of the list once it is found.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This scheme, handy for creating simple caches, ensures that the most recently used items are also the quickest to find again.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Another common approach is to "index" a linked list using a more efficient external data structure.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] For example, one can build a red–black tree or hash table whose elements are references to the linked list nodes.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Multiple such indexes can be built on a single list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The disadvantage is that these indexes may need to be updated each time a node is added or removed (or at least, before that index is used again).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A random-access list is a list with support for fast random access to read or modify any element in the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] One possible implementation is a skew binary random-access list using the skew binary number system, which involves a list of trees with special properties; this allows worst-case constant time head/cons operations, and worst-case logarithmic time random access to an element by index.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Random-access lists can be implemented as persistent data structures.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Random-access lists can be viewed as immutable linked lists in that they likewise support the same O(1) head and tail operations.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A simple extension to random-access lists is the min-list, which provides an additional operation that yields the minimum element in the entire list in constant time (without mutation complexities).
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Both stacks and queues are often implemented using linked lists, and simply restrict the type of operations which are supported.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The skip list is a linked list augmented with layers of pointers for quickly jumping over large numbers of elements, and then descending to the next layer.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This process continues down to the bottom layer, which is the actual list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A binary tree can be seen as a type of linked list where the elements are themselves linked lists of the same nature.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] The result is that each node may include a reference to the first node of one or two other linked lists, which, together with their contents, form the subtrees below that node.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] An unrolled linked list is a linked list in which each node contains an array of data values.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] This leads to improved cache performance, since more list elements are contiguous in memory, and reduced memory overhead, because less metadata needs to be stored for each element of the list.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A hash table may use linked lists to store the chains of items that hash to the same position in the hash table.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A heap shares some of the ordering properties of a linked list, but is almost always implemented using an array.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] Instead of references from node to node, the next and previous data indexes are calculated using the current data's index.
[src:data-structures/linked-list] A self-organizing list rearranges its nodes based on some heuristic which reduces search times for data retrieval by keeping commonly accessed nodes at the head of the list.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a queue is an abstract data type that serves as an ordered collection of entities.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] By convention, the end of the queue where elements are added is called the back, tail, or rear of the queue.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The end of the queue where elements are removed is called the head or front of the queue.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The name *queue* is an analogy to the words used to describe people in line to wait for goods or services.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Other operations may also be allowed, often including a *peek* or *front* operation that returns the value of the next element to be dequeued without dequeuing it.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The operations of a queue make it a first-in-first-out (FIFO) data structure as the first element added to the queue is the first one removed.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] This is equivalent to the requirement that once a new element is added, all elements that were added before have to be removed before the new element can be removed.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] A queue is an example of a linear data structure, or more abstractly a sequential collection.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Queues are common in computer programs, where they are implemented as data structures coupled with access routines, as an abstract data structure or in object-oriented languages as classes.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] A queue may be implemented as circular buffers and linked lists, or by using both the stack pointer and the base pointer.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Queues provide services in computer science, transport, and operations research where various entities such as data, objects, persons, or events are stored and held to be processed later.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] In these contexts, the queue performs the function of a buffer.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Another usage of queues is in the implementation of breadth-first search.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Theoretically, one characteristic of a queue is that it does not have a specific capacity.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Regardless of how many elements are already contained, a new element can always be added.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] It can also be empty, at which point removing an element will be impossible until a new element has been added again.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Fixed-length arrays are limited in capacity, but it is not true that items need to be copied towards the head of the queue.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The simple trick of turning the array into a closed circle and letting the head and tail drift around endlessly in that circle makes it unnecessary to ever move items stored in the array.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] If n is the size of the array, then computing indices modulo n will turn the array into a circle.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The array size must be declared ahead of time, but some implementations simply double the declared array size when overflow occurs.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Most modern languages with objects or pointers can implement or come with libraries for dynamic lists.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Such data structures may have not specified a fixed capacity limit besides memory constraints.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Queue *overflow* results from trying to add an element onto a full queue and queue *underflow* happens when trying to remove an element from an empty queue.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] A *bounded queue* is a queue limited to a fixed number of items.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] There are several efficient implementations of FIFO queues.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] An efficient implementation is one that can perform the operations—en-queuing and de-queuing—in O(1) time.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Queues may be implemented as a separate data type, or maybe considered a special case of a double-ended queue (deque) and not implemented separately.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] For example, Perl and Ruby allow pushing and popping an array from both ends, so one can use **push** and **shift** functions to enqueue and dequeue a list (or, in reverse, one can use **unshift** and **pop**), although in some cases these operations are not efficient.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] C++'s Standard Template Library provides a "`queue`" templated class which is restricted to only push/pop operations.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Since J2SE5.0, Java's library contains a `Queue` interface that specifies queue operations; implementing classes include `LinkedList` and (since J2SE 1.6) `ArrayDeque`.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] PHP has an SplQueue class and third-party libraries like beanstalk'd and Gearman.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Queues can also be implemented as a purely functional data structure.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The first one only achieves $O(1)$ per operation *on average*.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] That is, the amortized time is $O(1)$ , but individual operations can take $O(n)$ where *n* is the number of elements in the queue.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The second implementation is called a **real-time queue** and it allows the queue to be persistent with operations in O(1) worst-case time.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] It is a more complex implementation and requires lazy lists with memoization.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] This queue's data is stored in two singly-linked lists named f and r .
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The list f holds the front part of the queue.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The list r holds the remaining elements (a.k.a., the rear of the queue) *in reverse order*.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] It is easy to insert into the front of the queue by adding a node at the head of f .
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] And, if r is not empty, it is easy to remove from the end of the queue by removing the node at the head of r .
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] When r is empty, the list f is reversed and assigned to r and then the head of r is removed.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The insert ("enqueue") always takes $O(1)$ time.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The removal ("dequeue") takes $O(1)$ when the list r is not empty.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] When r is empty, the reverse takes $O(n)$ where n is the number of elements in f .
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] But, we can say it is $O(1)$ amortized time, because every element in f had to be inserted and we can assign a constant cost for each element in the reverse to when it was inserted.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The real-time queue achieves $O(1)$ time for all operations, without amortization.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] This discussion will be technical, so recall that, for l a list, $|l|$ denotes its length, that *NIL* represents an empty list and $\operatorname {CONS} (h,t)$ represents the list whose head is *h* and whose tail is *t*.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The data structure used to implement our queues consists of three singly-linked lists $(f,r,s)$ where *f* is the front of the queue and *r* is the rear of the queue in reverse order.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The invariant of the structure is that *s* is the rear of *f* without its $|r|$ first elements, that is $|s|=|f|-|r|$ .
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The tail of the queue $(\operatorname {CONS} (x,f),r,s)$ is then almost $(f,r,s)$ and inserting an element *x* to $(f,r,s)$ is almost $(f,\operatorname {CONS} (x,r),s)$ .
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] It is said almost, because in both of those results, $|s|=|f|-|r|+1$ .
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] An auxiliary function $aux$ must then be called for the invariant to be satisfied.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Two cases must be considered, depending on whether s is the empty list, in which case $|r|=|f|+1$ , or not.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Let us call $\operatorname {reverse} (f,r)$ the function which returns *f* followed by *r* reversed.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Let us furthermore assume that $|r|=|f|+1$ , since it is the case when this function is called.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] More precisely, we define a lazy function $\operatorname {rotate} (f,r,a)$ which takes as input three lists such that $|r|=|f|+1$ , and return the concatenation of *f*, of *r* reversed and of *a*.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Then $\operatorname {reverse} (f,r)=\operatorname {rotate} (f,r,{\text{NIL}})$ .
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Its running time is $O(r)$ , but, since lazy evaluation is used, the computation is delayed until the results are forced by the computation.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] The list *s* in the data structure has two purposes.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] This list serves as a counter for $|f|-|r|$ , indeed, $|f|=|r|$ if and only if *s* is the empty list.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] This counter allows us to ensure that the rear is never longer than the front list.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Furthermore, using *s*, which is a tail of *f*, forces the computation of a part of the (lazy) list *f* during each *tail* and *insert* operation.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] Therefore, when $|f|=|r|$ , the list *f* is totally forced.
[src:data-structures/queue-abstract-data-type] If it was not the case, the internal representation of *f* could be some append of append of... of append, and forcing would not be a constant time operation anymore.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] In computer science, a **skip list** (or **skiplist**) is a probabilistic data structure that allows ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ average complexity for search as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ average complexity for insertion within an ordered sequence of n elements.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Thus it can get the best features of a sorted array (for searching) while maintaining a linked list-like structure that allows insertion, which is not possible with a static array.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Fast search is made possible by maintaining a linked hierarchy of subsequences, with each successive subsequence skipping over fewer elements than the previous one *(see the picture below)*.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Searching starts in the sparsest subsequence until two consecutive elements have been found, one smaller and one larger than or equal to the element searched for.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Via the linked hierarchy, these two elements link to elements of the next sparsest subsequence, where searching is continued until finally searching in the full sequence.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] The elements that are skipped over may be chosen probabilistically or deterministically, with the former being more common.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] The bottom layer 1 is an ordinary ordered linked list.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Each higher layer acts as an "express lane" for the lists below, where an element in layer i appears in layer $i+1$ with some fixed probability p (two commonly used values for p are $1/2$ or $1/4$ ).
[src:data-structures/skip-list] On average, each element appears in $1/(1-p)$ lists, and the tallest element (usually a special head element at the front of the skip list) appears in all the lists.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] The skip list contains $\log _{1/p}n\,$ (i.e. logarithm base $1/p$ of n ) lists.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] A search for a target element begins at the head element in the top list, and proceeds horizontally until the current element is greater than or equal to the target.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] If the current element is equal to the target, it has been found.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] If the current element is greater than the target, or the search reaches the end of the linked list, the procedure is repeated after returning to the previous element and dropping down vertically to the next lower list.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] The expected number of steps in each linked list is at most $1/p$ , which can be seen by tracing the search path backwards from the target until reaching an element that appears in the next higher list or reaching the beginning of the current list.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Therefore, the total *expected* cost of a search is ${\tfrac {1}{p}}\log _{1/p}n$ which is ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)\,$ , when p is a constant.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] By choosing different values of p , it is possible to trade search costs against storage costs.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] For example, the value $p=1/e$ minimizes the average search time of skip lists, whereas the value $p=1/2$ simplifies their implementation.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] The elements used for a skip list can contain more than one pointer since they can participate in more than one list.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Insertions and deletions are implemented much like the corresponding linked-list operations, except that "tall" elements must be inserted into or deleted from more than one linked list.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] (Choose the level of the i'th finite node to be 1 plus the number of times it is possible to repeatedly divide i by 2 before it becomes odd.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Also, i=0 for the negative infinity header as there is the usual special case of choosing the highest possible level for negative and/or positive infinite nodes.) However this also allows someone to know where all of the higher-than-level 1 nodes are and delete them.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Like the derandomized version, quasi-randomization is only done when there is some other reason to be running an ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ operation (which visits every node).
[src:data-structures/skip-list] The advantage of this quasi-randomness is that it doesn't give away nearly as much level-structure related information to an adversarial user as the de-randomized one.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] This is desirable because an adversarial user who is able to tell which nodes are not at the lowest level can pessimize performance by simply deleting higher-level nodes.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] (Bethea and Reiter however argue that nonetheless an adversary can use probabilistic and timing methods to force performance degradation.) The search performance is still guaranteed to be logarithmic.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] It would be tempting to make the following "optimization": In the part which says "Next, for each *i*th...", forget about doing a coin-flip for each even-odd pair.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Just flip a coin once to decide whether to promote only the even ones or only the odd ones.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Instead of ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ coin flips, there would only be ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ of them.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Unfortunately, this gives the adversarial user a 50/50 chance of being correct upon guessing that all of the even numbered nodes (among the ones at level 1 or higher) are higher than level one.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] This is despite the property that there is a very low probability of guessing that a particular node is at level *N* for some integer *N*.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] A skip list does not provide the same absolute worst-case performance guarantees as more traditional balanced tree data structures, because it is always possible (though with very low probability) that the coin-flips used to build the skip list will produce a badly balanced structure.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] However, they work well in practice, and the randomized balancing scheme has been argued to be easier to implement than the deterministic balancing schemes used in balanced binary search trees.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Skip lists are also useful in parallel computing, where insertions can be done in different parts of the skip list in parallel without any global rebalancing of the data structure.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Such parallelism can be especially advantageous for resource discovery in an ad-hoc wireless network because a randomized skip list can be made robust to the loss of any single node.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] For every link, also store the width of the link.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] The width is defined as the number of bottom layer links being traversed by each of the higher layer "express lane" links.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Notice that the width of a higher level link is the sum of the component links below it (i.e. the width 10 link spans the links of widths 3, 2 and 5 immediately below it).
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Consequently, the sum of all widths is the same on every level (10 + 1 = 1 + 3 + 2 + 5 = 1 + 2 + 1 + 2 + 3 + 2).
[src:data-structures/skip-list] To index the skip list and find the i'th value, traverse the skip list while counting down the widths of each traversed link.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Descend a level whenever the upcoming width would be too large.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] For example, to find the node in the fifth position (Node 5), traverse a link of width 1 at the top level.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Now four more steps are needed but the next width on this level is ten which is too large, so drop one level.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Since another step of width 2 would be too far, drop down to the bottom level.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Now traverse the final link of width 1 to reach the target running total of 5 (1+3+1).
[src:data-structures/skip-list] Skip lists were first described in 1989 by William Pugh.
[src:data-structures/skip-list] There are also several US patents for using skip lists to implement (lockless) priority queues and concurrent dictionaries.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Additionally, a peek operation can, without modifying the stack, return the value of the last element added (the item at the top of the stack).
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The name *stack* is an analogy to a set of physical items stacked one atop another, such as a stack of plates.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The order in which elements are added to or removed from a stack is described as **last in, first out**, referred to by the acronym **LIFO**.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] As with a stack of physical objects, this structure makes it easy to take an item off the top of the stack, but accessing a datum deeper in the stack may require removing multiple other items first.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Considered a sequential collection, a stack has one end which is the only position at which the push and pop operations may occur, the *top* of the stack, and is fixed at the other end, the *bottom*.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack may be implemented as, for example, a singly linked list with a pointer to the top element.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack may be implemented to have a bounded capacity.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] If the stack is full and does not contain enough space to accept another element, the stack is in a state of stack overflow.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks entered the computer science literature in 1946, when Alan Turing used the terms "bury" and "unbury" as a means of calling and returning from subroutines.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Subroutines and a two-level stack had already been implemented in Konrad Zuse's Z4 in 1945.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Bauer of the Technical University of Munich proposed the idea of a stack called *Operationskeller* ("operational cellar") in 1955 and filed a patent in 1957.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] In March 1988, by which time Samelson was deceased, Bauer received the IEEE Computer Pioneer Award for the invention of the stack principle.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Similar concepts were independently developed by Charles Leonard Hamblin in the first half of 1954 and by Wilhelm Kämmerer with his *automatisches Gedächtnis* ("automatic memory") in 1958.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks are often described using the analogy of a spring-loaded stack of plates in a cafeteria.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Clean plates are placed on top of the stack, pushing down any plates already there.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] When the top plate is removed from the stack, the one below it is elevated to become the new top plate.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] In many implementations, a stack has more operations than the essential "push" and "pop" operations.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] An example of a non-essential operation is "top of stack", or "peek", which observes the top element without removing it from the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Since this can be broken down into a "pop" followed by a "push" to return the same data to the stack, it is not considered an essential operation.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] If the stack is empty, an underflow condition will occur upon execution of either the "peek" or "pop" operation.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Additionally, many implementations include convenience operations that handle common tasks, such as checking if the stack is empty or returning its size.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack can be easily implemented either through an array or a linked list, as it is merely a special case of a list.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] In either case, what identifies the data structure as a stack is not the implementation but the interface: the user is only allowed to pop or push items onto the array or linked list, with few other helper operations.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The following will demonstrate both implementations using pseudocode.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] An array can be used to implement a (bounded) stack, as follows.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The first element, usually at the zero offset, is the bottom, resulting in `array[0]` being the first element pushed onto the stack and the last element popped off.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The program must keep track of the size (length) of the stack, using a variable *top* that records the number of items pushed so far, therefore pointing to the place in the array where the next element is to be inserted (assuming a zero-based index convention).
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Using a dynamic array, it is possible to implement a stack that can grow or shrink as much as needed.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The size of the stack is simply the size of the dynamic array, which is a very efficient implementation of a stack since adding items to or removing items from the end of a dynamic array requires amortized O(1) time.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Another option for implementing stacks is to use a singly linked list.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Some languages, such as Perl, LISP, JavaScript and Python, make the stack operations push and pop available on their standard list/array types.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Some languages, notably those in the Forth family (including PostScript), are designed around language-defined stacks that are directly visible to and manipulated by the programmer.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Several of the C++ Standard Library container types have `push_back()` and `pop_back()` operations with LIFO semantics; additionally, the `std::stack` template class adapts existing containers to provide a restricted API with only push/pop operations.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Java's library contains a `Stack` class that is a specialization of `Vector`.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Following is an example program in Java language, using that class.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Some processors, such as the PDP-11, VAX, and Motorola 68000 series have addressing modes useful for stack manipulation.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The following trivial PDP-11 assembly source code pushes two numbers on a stack and adds them, leaving the result on the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A common use of stacks at the architecture level is as a means of allocating and accessing memory.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A typical stack is an area of computer memory with a fixed origin and a variable size.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Initially the size of the stack is zero.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack pointer (usually in the form of a processor register) points to the most recently referenced location on the stack; when the stack has a size of zero, the stack pointer points to the origin of the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] There are many variations on the basic principle of stack operations.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Every stack has a fixed location in memory at which it begins.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] As data items are added to the stack, the stack pointer is displaced to indicate the current extent of the stack, which expands away from the origin.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Stack pointers may point to the origin of a stack or to a limited range of addresses above or below the origin (depending on the direction in which the stack grows); however, the stack pointer cannot cross the origin of the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] In other words, if the origin of the stack is at address 1000 and the stack grows downwards (towards addresses 999, 998, and so on), the stack pointer must never be incremented beyond 1000 (to 1001 or beyond).
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] If a pop operation on the stack causes the stack pointer to move past the origin of the stack, a *stack underflow* occurs.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] If a push operation causes the stack pointer to increment or decrement beyond the maximum extent of the stack, a *stack overflow* occurs.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks are often visualized growing from the bottom up (like real-world stacks).
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] They may also be visualized growing from left to right, where the top is on the far right, or even growing from top to bottom.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The important feature is for the bottom of the stack to be in a fixed position.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The illustration in this section is an example of a top-to-bottom growth visualization: the top (28) is the stack "bottom", since the stack "top" (9) is where items are pushed or popped from.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A *right rotate* will move the first element to the third position, the second to the first and the third to the second.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack is usually represented in computers by a block of memory cells, with the "bottom" at a fixed location, and the stack pointer holding the address of the current "top" cell in the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The "top" and "bottom" nomenclature is used irrespective of whether the stack actually grows towards higher memory addresses.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Pushing an item on to the stack adjusts the stack pointer by the size of the item (either decrementing or incrementing, depending on the direction in which the stack grows in memory), pointing it to the next cell, and copies the new top item to the stack area.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Depending again on the exact implementation, at the end of a push operation, the stack pointer may point to the next unused location in the stack, or it may point to the topmost item in the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] If the stack points to the current topmost item, the stack pointer will be updated before a new item is pushed onto the stack; if it points to the next available location in the stack, it will be updated *after* the new item is pushed onto the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Popping the stack is simply the inverse of pushing.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The topmost item in the stack is removed and the stack pointer is updated, in the opposite order of that used in the push operation.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Many CISC-type CPU designs, including the x86, Z80 and 6502, have a dedicated register for use as the call stack stack pointer with dedicated call, return, push, and pop instructions that implicitly update the dedicated register, thus increasing code density.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Some CISC processors, like the PDP-11 and the 68000, also have special addressing modes for implementation of stacks, typically with a semi-dedicated stack pointer as well (such as A7 in the 68000).
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] In contrast, most RISC CPU designs do not have dedicated stack instructions and therefore most, if not all, registers may be used as stack pointers as needed.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Some machines use a stack for arithmetic and logical operations; operands are pushed onto the stack, and arithmetic and logical operations act on the top one or more items on the stack, popping them off the stack and pushing the result onto the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Machines that function in this fashion are called stack machines.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A number of mainframes and minicomputers were stack machines, the most famous being the Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Other examples include the CISC HP 3000 machines and the CISC machines from Tandem Computers.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The x87 floating-point architecture is an example of a set of registers organised as a stack where direct access to individual registers (relative to the current top) is also possible.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Having the top-of-stack as an implicit argument allows for a small machine code footprint with a good usage of bus bandwidth and code caches, but it also prevents some types of optimizations possible on processors permitting random access to the register file for all (two or three) operands.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack structure also makes superscalar implementations with register renaming (for speculative execution) somewhat more complex to implement, although it is still feasible, as exemplified by modern x87 implementations.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Sun SPARC, AMD Am29000, and Intel i960 are all examples of architectures that use register windows within a register-stack as another strategy to avoid the use of slow main memory for function arguments and return values.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] There is also a number of small microprocessors that implement a stack directly in hardware, and some microcontrollers have a fixed-depth stack that is not directly accessible.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Examples are the PIC microcontrollers, the Computer Cowboys MuP21, the Harris RTX line, and the Novix NC4016.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] At least one microcontroller family, the COP400, implements a stack either directly in hardware or in RAM via a stack pointer, depending on the device.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Many stack-based microprocessors were used to implement the programming language Forth at the microcode level.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Calculators that employ reverse Polish notation use a stack structure to hold values.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Expressions can be represented in prefix, postfix or infix notations and conversion from one form to another may be accomplished using a stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Many compilers use a stack to parse syntax before translation into low-level code.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Most programming languages are context-free languages, allowing them to be parsed with stack-based machines.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Another important application of stacks is backtracking.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] An illustration of this is the simple example of finding the correct path in a maze that contains a series of points, a starting point, several paths and a destination.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] If random paths must be chosen, then after following an incorrect path, there must be a method by which to return to the beginning of that path.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] This can be achieved through the use of stacks, as a last correct point can be pushed onto the stack, and popped from the stack in case of an incorrect path.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The prototypical example of a backtracking algorithm is depth-first search, which finds all vertices of a graph that can be reached from a specified starting vertex.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Other applications of backtracking involve searching through spaces that represent potential solutions to an optimization problem.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Branch and bound is a technique for performing such backtracking searches without exhaustively searching all of the potential solutions in such a space.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] A number of programming languages are stack-oriented, meaning they define most basic operations (adding two numbers, printing a character) as taking their arguments from the stack, and placing any return values back on the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] For example, PostScript has a return stack and an operand stack, and also has a graphics state stack and a dictionary stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Many virtual machines are also stack-oriented, including the p-code machine and the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The functions follow a runtime protocol between caller and callee to save arguments and return value on the stack.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks are an important way of supporting nested or recursive function calls.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] This type of stack is used implicitly by the compiler to support CALL and RETURN statements (or their equivalents) and is not manipulated directly by the programmer.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Some programming languages use the stack to store data that is local to a procedure.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Space for local data items is allocated from the stack when the procedure is entered, and is deallocated when the procedure exits.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] The C programming language is typically implemented in this way.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Using the same stack for both data and procedure calls has important security implications (see below) of which a programmer must be aware in order to avoid introducing serious security bugs into a program.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Several algorithms use a stack (separate from the usual function call stack of most programming languages) as the principal data structure with which they organize their information.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Some computing environments use stacks in ways that may make them vulnerable to security breaches and attacks.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Programmers working in such environments must take special care to avoid such pitfalls in these implementations.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] As an example, some programming languages use a common stack to store both data local to a called procedure and the linking information that allows the procedure to return to its caller.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] This means that the program moves data into and out of the same stack that contains critical return addresses for the procedure calls.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] If data is moved to the wrong location on the stack, or an oversized data item is moved to a stack location that is not large enough to contain it, return information for procedure calls may be corrupted, causing the program to fail.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Malicious parties may attempt a stack smashing attack that takes advantage of this type of implementation by providing oversized data input to a program that does not check the length of input.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Such a program may copy the data in its entirety to a location on the stack, and in doing so, it may change the return addresses for procedures that have called it.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] This type of attack is a variation on the buffer overflow attack and is an extremely frequent source of security breaches in software, mainly because some of the most popular compilers use a shared stack for both data and procedure calls, and do not verify the length of data items.
[src:data-structures/stack-abstract-data-type] Frequently, programmers do not write code to verify the size of data items, either, and when an oversized or undersized data item is copied to the stack, a security breach may occur.
[src:data-structures/trie] In computer science, a **trie** (/ˈtraɪ/, /ˈtriː/ ⓘ), also known as a **digital tree** or **prefix tree**, is a specialized search tree data structure used to store and retrieve strings from a dictionary or set.
[src:data-structures/trie] Unlike a binary search tree, nodes in a trie do not store their associated key.
[src:data-structures/trie] Instead, each node's *position* within the trie determines its associated key, with the connections between nodes defined by individual characters rather than the entire key.
[src:data-structures/trie] Tries are particularly effective for tasks such as autocomplete, spell checking, and IP routing, offering advantages over hash tables due to their prefix-based organization and lack of hash collisions.
[src:data-structures/trie] Every child node shares a common prefix with its parent node, and the root node represents the empty string.
[src:data-structures/trie] While basic trie implementations can be memory-intensive, various optimization techniques such as compression and bitwise representations have been developed to improve their efficiency.
[src:data-structures/trie] A notable optimization is the radix tree, which provides more efficient prefix-based storage.
[src:data-structures/trie] While tries store character strings, they can be adapted to work with any ordered sequence of elements, such as permutations of digits or shapes.
[src:data-structures/trie] A notable variant is the **bitwise trie**, which uses individual bits from fixed-length binary data (such as integers or memory addresses) as keys.
[src:data-structures/trie] The idea of a trie for representing a set of strings was first abstractly described by Axel Thue in 1912.
[src:data-structures/trie] Tries were first described in a computer context by René de la Briandais in 1959.
[src:data-structures/trie] The idea was independently described in 1960 by Edward Fredkin, who coined the term *trie*, pronouncing it /ˈtriː/ (as "tree"), after the middle syllable of *retrieval*.
[src:data-structures/trie] However, other authors pronounce it /ˈtraɪ/ (as "try"), in an attempt to distinguish it verbally from "tree".
[src:data-structures/trie] Tries are a form of string-indexed look-up data structure, which is used to store a dictionary list of words that can be searched on in a manner that allows for efficient generation of completion lists.
